<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-Campaign     05-29 0757</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Campaign,0781</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidate Sounds Like Reformer In Final Weeks Of Presidential
Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At times, Carlos Salinas de Gortari sounds
too much like a reformer to be the presidential candidate of the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, which has governed Mexico since
1929.
   The 40-year-old candidate preaches democratic reforms and clean
elections as he campaigns not so much for the office, which he is
certain to win, but to regain his party's lost credibility.
   Salinas de Gortari, whose thick black moustache and balding head
feature prominently in political cartoons, is described by those
close to him as a pragmatist, influenced strongly by his Harvard
education.
   Before his nomination last fall as a candidate in the July 6
election, he was President Miguel de La Madrid's budget and
planning secretary, a key figure in developing the economic
austerity programs that have prevailed in Mexico since 1982.
   Salinas de Gortari has strong family ties to the northern state
of Nuevo Leon, home to political conservatives who oppose the
guided economy and government controls dear to governing party
ideologues in Mexico City.
   Some foes within the party felt Salinas de Gortari would be
identified too strongly with the business sector and with
conservative groups within the party.
   But this has worked to the party's advantage. Salinas de Gortari
has managed to bring private business back into the party fold by
advocating fewer government controls and urging business leaders to
join the government ``in the battle for world markets.''
   ``The time is past when the state was the instrument to solve
all of society's problems,'' he told a cheering crowd at a recent
meeting of business leaders in Monterrey, Nuevo Leon's capital.
   He also wants more foreign investment to ``modernize Mexico
technologically.''
   ``What he says agrees with what private business thinks Mexico
must be,'' said Agustin Legorreta, president of the Business
Coordinating Council.
   Mexican business traditionally has identified with the
conservative National Action Party, although it must maintain a
close relationship with government agencies.
   Salinas de Gortari speaks confidently of the resurgence of
Mexico. The country has a $105 billion foreign debt but has
renegotiated it and is keeping up payments.
   Last month in Puebla, a politically conservative state in
central Mexico, Salinas de Gortari upset some party officials with
his call for reforms.
   ``The citizens' vote must be respected,'' he said. ``The party
will defend its victories, but it must accept its defeats.''
   He also promised reforms to encourage more independent judiciary
and legislative branches.
   ``Let us lead the democratic reform the country demands,'' he
stated.
   The political reforms may be difficult because they imply the
acceptance by the PRI of electoral losses and the consequent loss
of power of local or regional party bosses.
   The party never has lost a presidential election or
gubernatorial race in any of Mexico's 31 states since its founding.
   It is generally conceded in Mexico that the governing party wins
elections, but it often is criticized for ``winning'' by more than
the necessary votes _ by stuffing ballots to claim overwhelming
victories.
   ``There is a great internal debate going on now,'' said a source
close to the candidate. ``Salinas de Gortari is demanding elections
free of fraud and there is a lot of pressure being put on local
party leaders to be more democratic.''
   This year, with the country in the middle of a serious economic
crisis, and an increasingly vociferous opposition that includes a
dissident group led by former party leaders, those close to Salinas
de Gortari believe reforms have a good chance in his six-year term.
   ``It is better in the long run to win by a small margin than to
announce we won by a large margin and lose all credibility,'' said
a source in Salinas' entourage during a recent campaign trip.
   Some PRI officials privately admit the party may even lose a
Senate seat, something that has never happened before.
   De la Madrid won the elections in 1982 for the PRI with an
official 71 percent of the vote, a figure many considered
exaggerated. PRI officials now predict Salinas de Gortari may win
the July 6 election with a more realistic 55 percent to 60 percent
of the votes.
   ``We do not know if he will have the freedom to do what he wants
to do,'' said Alejandro Junco, publisher of the newspaper El Norte
of Monterrey and a frequent government critic. ``But we are
condemned to be optimistic evey six years.''
</TEXT>
