<HEAD>Search Continues for Three Missing in Fatal Boating Accident</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE number of dead to two, search
suspended, missing presumed dead; picks up 5th graf: ``Most of .. .</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OCEAN CITY, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drowning, a missing swimmer, and a
boating accident that killed two people, injured five and left two
men missing and presumed dead marked this seaside resort's Memorial
Day weekend.
   Searches continued until Sunday night for a missing 16-year-old
boy who apparently was caught by undertow Saturday afternoon, and
for two men still missing from the boating accident late Saturday
night, authorities said.
   One woman was killed when an 19-foot boat carrying seven
passengers plowed into an anchored, 25-foot boat with two aboard
about a quarter-mile north of Ocean City, said Ralph Parker, a
Maryland Natural Resources Police spokesman.
   The seven were ejected into the water and none was wearing a
lifejacket, authorities said. Searchers found the body of a second
victim around 8 p.m. Sunday about 300 yards from the collision
site, officers said.
   The two men still missing were presumed dead, officials said.
   ``Most of the injuries seem to be impact injuries,'' said Sgt.
Michael Bloxom of the Natural Resources Police.``And there's a
possibility some of them might not have known how to swim.''
   Authorities would give no further details other than that a
23-year-old Baltimore woman died at the scene and five people were
taken to hospitals.
   The names of all nine people were withheld until relatives were
notified. Authorities confiscated both boats, but issued no
citations pending completion of the investigation.
   The 16-year-old Pennsylvania boy was reported missing Saturday
afternoon after he and a friend went swimming and were caught in
the undertow. The friend reached shore and alerted lifeguards.
   A search by Ocean City police, the beach patrol, the Coast Guard
and a state police helicopter Saturday turned up no trace of the
youth, whose name was not released.
   Around 8:30 a.m. Saturday, Robert S. Hinkleman, 28, of Glen
Burnie, apparently drowned in the surf, 90 minutes before
lifeguards went on duty for the first time in the beach season,
police said.
</TEXT>
