<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-88 0004EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-B-52Rocket     05-29 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-B-52 Rocket,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Plans Experimental Rocket Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon plans to build an experimental
rocket that would be dropped from a B-52 bomber and used to launch
military satellites into space, a newspaper reported Sunday.
   The three-stage, winged rocket would be dropped about seven
miles above the earth and then blast into space, placing payloads
of up to 600 pounds into orbit, The New York Times reported,
quoting government and industry experts.
   Officials have said they hope a prototype will fly next year.
   The Pentagon wants to test the rocket for a program designed to
develop light-weight satellites and launchers for various military
uses, including spy and communication satellites.
   The experimental rocket is being pursued by the Defense Advanced
Research Projects Agency, which develops futuristic projects for
the Pentagon.
   There is concern on Capitol Hill that the rocket could be
launched in secrecy, the Times reported.
   Although there is an agreement requiring space-faring countries
to notify the United Nations of all payloads going into orbit, the
rocket could be fired from remote parts of the world, far from
Soviet trawlers and spy satellites that monitor military launchings
from the United States.
   The Pentagon has given no indication that it would violate the
treaty obligation, but some military officials say privately that
it would be useful for the United States to have the option of
quick, secret launchings in the event of war.
   The Lightsat program, which includes the rocket, is part of a
five-year, $240 million effort.
   On May 13, the Pentagon signed a letter of contractual intent
with Orbital Sciences to buy one test rocket, with an option for
five more, industry sources say. Orbital Sciences would be joined
by Hercules, Inc. which makes solid-fuel rockets.
   The three-stage, solid-fuel rocket would weigh 15 tons and
measure 50 feet in length.
   Proponents say the air-launched rocket system would be
inexpensive, less vulnerable to attack than ground-based spaceports
and ideal for quickly launching small spy satellites to monitor
fast-moving battles.
   Donald C. Latham, a former assistant secretary of defense, said:
``The nation looked into air-launched rockets 20 years ago and
found them wanting. There are better ways to make systems low cost
and survivable.''
</TEXT>
