<DOCNO> AP880529-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-88 1141EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-Cambodia     05-29 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-Cambodia,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Khmer Rouge Denounce Vietnamese Withdrawal from Cambodia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Khmer Rouge guerrillas denounced as
``stinking and deceitful'' an announcement by Vietnam that it would
pull 50,000 troops from Cambodia this year, according to a
broadcast made available Sunday.
   A communique released Saturday by the Khmer Rouge military
command said Hanoi actually was shifting its troops around Cambodia
in a frantic attempt to counter escalating guerrilla attacks.
   Vietnam, which invaded Cambodia in late 1978, is fighting a
coalition of three resistance groups including the communist Khmer
Rouge. On Thursday, it announced a partial pullout of 50,000 troops
to be followed by a total withdrawal in 1990.
   Vietnam says it has made annual withdrawals since 1982, but the
United States says the only genuine pullout was in November, when
20,000 troops were withdrawn.
   The United States estimates Vietnam still has 120,000 to 125,000
troops in Cambodia and says the other troop movements were only
rotations.
   Vietnam and the pro-Hanoi regime in Cambodia said better
security in the country made possible the Vietnamese reduction
scheduled to begin next month.
   But the Khmer Rouge communique, broadcast over the clandestine
Khmer Rouge radio, said Vietnam this month has been ``moving troops
back and forth from one battlefield to another aimlessly like a
frightened monkey'' to withstand guerrilla strikes. It called the
claim ``stinking and deceitful.''
   ``There is no sign that the Vietnamese enemy is preparing to
withdraw 50,000 troops from Cambodia,'' the communique said. ``This
is more shameless propaganda to deceive world public opinion.''
   The communique cited details of what it claimed to be Vietnamese
troop movements in recent months.
   Western analysts regard Khmer Rouge claims with suspicion and
most are not verified by independent sources.
   On Saturday, China also said the Vietnamese claims of troop
withdrawal were deceptive.
   The Khmer Rouge is the most powerful of three rebel groups in a
coalition led by Prince Norodom Sihanouk. Announcements of the
Vietnamese withdrawal have sparked some fears that the Khmer Rouge
could return to power.
   The Khmer Rouge ruled Cambodia from 1975 until the Vietnamese
invasion. Millions of Cambodians were killed or died of starvation
or disease in the regime's attempt to impose radical agrarian
communism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
