<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     05-29 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Dead in Assassination Attempt; Three Indian Soldiers Slain In
Ambush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese extremists opened fire with
automatic rifles at the home of a politician and killed six people,
including the politician's 10-year-old daughter, police said Sunday.
   In northern Sri Lanka, Tamil rebels ambushed a convoy of Indian
troops and killed at least three soldiers, residents said.
   The politician, K.W.R. Dharmasena, his wife and three supporters
were injured in the assassination attempt late Saturday night, said
a police officer, who spoke on condition of anonymity in accordance
with police regulations.
   He said the dead included Dharmasena's daughter and his father.
The other victims, all men, were relatives of Dharmasena, he said.
   The attack occurred in the town of Homagama, 12 miles southeast
of Colombo.
   Earlier Saturday, an opposition party candidate and two of his
supporters were shot to death by suspected Sinhalese nationalists
in the town of Natala, 65 miles northeast of Colombo.
   They were the latest in a series of attacks blamed on the
People's Liberation Front, an underground group of nationalist
Sinhalese opposed to an accord signed last July to end violence by
Tamil separatists.
   The Tamil ambush in the northern district of Vavuniya killed
three soldiers and wounded at least five other Indian troops, said
residents who spoke on condition of anonymity. They did not know of
any rebel casualties.
   There was no comment from the Indian government.
   At least 50,000 Indian soldiers have been deployed in Sri Lanka
to disarm Tamil rebels who renounced the peace accord. India, which
as a large Tamil population of its own, sponsored the accord. The
plan calls for Tamils to lay down their arms in exchange for the
creation of district councils.
   Sinhalese extremists contend the pact makes too many concessions
to the Tamils, who are fighting for a separate homeland.
   Dharmasena is a candidate from the governing United National
Party for elections scheduled next Thursday.
   At least 19 candidates have been killed by the Sinhalese front
in the past two months, and there have been 12 assassination
attempts on candidates.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's
16 million population. They claim they are discriminated against by
the majority Sinhalese Buddhists, who control the government and
military.

</TEXT>
