<HEAD>Explosion Rips Through Mosque in Northern Greece</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KOMOTINI, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded in a Moslem mosque in
this northern town early Sunday, damaging its interior and
shattering windows of neighboring buildings. Police said no one was
injured.
   Police said a gasoline bomb was tossed into another mosque in
the area 15 minutes later, sparking a fire that was immediately
extinguished.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility for the attacks.
   A police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
bomb was placed at the mosque's entrance.
   About half of Komotini's 35,000 residents are Moslems. The town
in the province of Thrace is about 35 miles west of the Turkish
border.
   The attacks came two days after political cooperation talks
ended in Athens between senior Greek officials and a Turkish
delegation led by Foreign Minister Mesut Yilmaz.
   Relations between the two countries have improved since premiers
Andreas Papandreou of Greece and Turgut Ozal of Turkey met in
Davos, Switzerland, in January.
   Another meeting between the two leaders is scheduled in the
Greek capital June 13.
