<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bangladesh-Floods     05-29 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh-Floods,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Dead, Thousands Displaced by Flooding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least five people have died and
thousands have been forced to flee their homes because of flooding
in Bangladesh's northeastern districts, government officials and
news reports said Sunday.
   Last summer, more than one-quarter of the nation's 105 million
people were forced to flee the worst flooding in 70 years.
   This year, heavy rains and the annual snow melt from the
Himalaya mountains have sent the Surma and Kushiara rivers in the
northeastern districts of Sylhet and Sunamganj over their banks.
   Government officials in Sylhet, 100 miles northeast of Dhaka,
said Sunday that three people died when their house was washed away
and that two others drowned.
   The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said at
least 30,000 people have been marooned. Thousands of others made
their way to relief camps and were being aided by local Red Cross
officers and government agencies.
   The government-owned Bengalai-language Dainik Bangla newspaper
said at least 500,000 people had been driven from their homes
during the past week of rain and flooding.
   Thousands of acres of tea plantations and rice paddies were
reported inundated. Rice is a staple food in Bangladesh.
   Some market towns in Sunamganj District were reported under two
feet of water.
   Schools in both districts have been closed, and some have been
converted to relief centers for the homeless, the officials said.
   The government officials said flights were disrupted at the
airport at Sylhet on Saturday.
   Last year, two months of serious flooding killed about 1,500
people and destroyed thousands of acres of crops.
</TEXT>
