<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Hayden     05-29 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Hayden,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tom Hayden Discusses His Life and Politics at Book Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California legislator Tom Hayden, the
former radical protest leader, said at a booksellers' convention he
has revised his thinking about the death penalty.
   While being questioned about his recently published book,
``Reunion: A Memoir,'' Hayden was asked Saturday if he's withdrawn
his opposition to the death penalty.
   ``I've come to a kind of tortured conclusion that I'm not going
to lead a fight to repeal the death penalty,'' said Hayden, a
Democratic Assemblyman who represents Santa Monica.
   ``We live in a society in Calfornia that is very open and very
violent,'' Hayden said. ``People who commit murders are generally
in prison about eight years and then they are back on the streets.
Until that is corrected, I'm not going to oppose the death
penalty.''
   Hayden, who is married to actress Jane Fonda, was at the 88th
annual convention of the American Booksellers Association to
promote his book, published by Random House.
   In ``Reunion,'' Hayden looks back at the political turbulence of
the 1960s as the beginning of his disillusionment with government,
then follows through to a renewal of his faith in government
growing out of the Watergate scandal.
   ``It's a story that began as a history and it became more
personal as time went on because I was searching for truth about
the '60s and about my youth,'' Hayden said.
   Hayden said he believed in the 1960s that America was drifting
toward a police state.
   But after Watergate, ``I had to try to understand that many of
the people who had tried to put me in jail had failed and were
going to jail themselves.''
</TEXT>
