<DOCNO> AP880529-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-88 1159EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ConventionTroubles Bjt   05-29 0910</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Convention Troubles, Bjt,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Try to Dispel Image of Chaos in Convention Preparations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats were elated with the photo, buried
in the B-section of The New York Times, of a crane installing media
booths in the hall that will host the party's convention this
summer.
   ``It's the appearance of motion ... Things looked like they were
screwed up and now it looks like things are happening,'' party
spokesman Mike McCurry said, only half in jest as he referred to
the convention's public relations debacle of a week earlier.
   McCurry quickly added that the Atlanta convention plans are in
fact on track, following a press walkthrough two weeks ago that
left media representatives with a sinking feeling that things were
nightmarishly behind schedule.
   The party is scurrying to undo the perception that their July
18-21 presidential nominating convention will be a logistics
disaster, and moving to keep that perception from becoming reality.
   By way of damage control, convention Chairman Don Fowler rushed
out a letter to all media organizations promising the staff is
``vigorously pursuing appropriate action'' to respond to questions
that went unanswered at the walkthrough.
   He promised a press packet June 1 to include such information as
a critical vendor list, for necessities like furniture and
utilities. Such a list went out about a month earlier at the
party's 1984 convention.
   Written materials and informed staff members were on hand to
reassure the press at a second walkthrough a few days later that
their concerns are being handled on such matters as housing,
vendors and ``turnaround credentials'' that allow reporters to give
their pass to a colleague when leaving the floor.
   Emphasis is being placed on the fact there will be an increase
of 10 to 15 percent above 1984 numbers of media credentials issued.
   Convention veteran Wally Podrazik, who has handled media
logistics in past years was brought on board the day of the first
walkthrough, and this weekend will be joined by Cynthia Myers to
help with media arrangements.
   The person responsible for the media-tour foul-up was ousted,
and McCurry, who headed the Democratic National Committee press
office, has assumed overall responsibility as communications
director for both the party and the convention.
   ``We're in a lot better shape than many people suspect,''
McCurry insisted.
   He and others involved with the convention say the basics _
housing, transportation and credentials _ are more or less
arranged. But the staff members knowledgeable on those matters were
not at the first media tour on May 16.
   ``It is fair to say we did not put our best foot forward in that
walkthrough,'' said convention press secretary Ruth Berry.
   The presidential campaigns of Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson,
however, say they are having no problems as they embark on their
own convention preparations.
   ``All the things we feel we need to do are getting done,'' said
Dukakis spokesman Leslie Dach.
   Jackson logistics manager John O'Leary said he has had nothing
but cooperation, and ``It's basically a wide open door of
information'' from the convention officials.
   But O'Leary, a veteran convention staffer who managed the hall
for the 1984 convention in San Francisco, also said he sees the
Atlanta operation as comparatively behind schedule even in light of
his observation that ``Democratic conventions are inherently
complicated disorganized functions.''
   ``I wish they would have picked up a greater number of
experienced people earlier,'' said O'Leary. ``The convention will
happen. It's just a question of how much pain and grief will be
suffered and by whom.''
   He noted the drumbeat of concerns being voiced about the size of
the Omni basketball arena, which will seat 11,000, compared to the
15,000 seating capacity in 1984 at the Moscone Center Hall.
   The Democrats have solved the problem _ providing comparatively
more total seating _ by using the Georgia World Congress Center,
across the street from the Omni, for media workspace, spillover
viewing areas via large screens, and office and reception rooms.
   But that does not mean that spectators and party bigwigs are
going to be happy being relegated to watching the convention from
across the street.
   The Democrats are doing a hard sell to make the WCC seem an
attractive alternative. There, said McCurry, people can sprawl out
in comfort instead of being squished in the crowded Omni, and ``be
handed a refreshment by a young Democrat.''
   ``We are going to be agressively promoting the World Congress
Center as a place to hold meetings and briefings and press
conferences,'' he said.
   As for the Omni, everyone sighed with relief last week when the
Atlanta Hawks were edged out of the National Basketball Association
playoffs. That assured they would not tie up the Omni convention
hall until late June.
   ``Thank God the Celtics beat the Hawks,'' said Marcia Hale, in
charge of Dukakis campaign convention arrangements.
   The Omni is now available, but an access problem remains for the
World Congress Center which is booked with a trade convention until
the first of July.
   Because of that, the media trailers, cables and arrangements
that normally would be done over six or seven weeks will have to be
completed in just over two weeks, said Jeff Gralnick, vice
president and executive producer of special programming for ABC
News.
   Gralnick was philosophical about the foul-up, noting the
Republican convention in New Orleans has had no such problems, but
that, ``It's axiomatic that Republicans are more organized than
Democrats.''
</TEXT>
