<1ST_LINE>r p AM-AustinMayor     05-29 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Austin Mayor,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Incumbent Loses in Austin Mayoral Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former City Councilman Lee Cooke handily
defeated incumbent Mayor Frank Cooksey in his bid for a second
three-year term, besting the mayor by more than 15 percent of the
vote in a weekend runoff.
   Turnout for Saturday's election was put at about 20 percent by
City Clerk Elden Aldridge, who said: ``It's a lower turnout than
anything we have had in a number of years. I would say it's lower
because of Memorial Day weekend and people scattered here and
there.''
   With all the vote in, Cooke had 36,985 votes, or 58.4 percent,
to 26,308, or 41.6 percent, for Cooksey.
   Cooke, 43, a former president of this capital city's Chamber of
Commerce, captured 40 percent of the vote in the May 7 non-partisan
primary to advance to the runoff against Cooksey, 54, who ran
second in the field of eight with 32 percent.
   At issue in the campaign were the city's sagging economy and
rising taxes and utility rates.
   Austin was caught in an economic downturn several months into
Cooksey's first term and ``fairly or unfairly the business
community regarded him as their mortal enemy,'' said Dean Rindy,
Cooksey's media adviser.
   ``Frank had the misfortune to get elected mayor of Disneyland
just when the power got cut off,'' Rindy said.
   During the campaign, Cooksey tried to emphasize his
accomplishments, many of them in the environmental area, such as
the passage of bonds to clean up sewage discharge and the
implementation of a watershed ordinance.
   Cooke, meanwhile, blamed the downturn in the economy on Cooksey
and said the City Council, with Cooksey in the lead, was not doing
enough to keep the budget in line and attract businesses to Austin.
   He is reported to have spent $364,000 on his mayoral bid to
$272,000 by Cooksey.
</TEXT>
