<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mother Teresa says she would
like to build a hospice for AIDS patients in Vancouver similar to
facilities she has started in the United States.
   ``Our brothers and sisters suffering from AIDS are the people
that need very tender, loving care,'' the Nobel Peace Prize-winning
nun told reporters Saturday at Vancouver International Airport.
   She said she was in Vancouver ``to help the poorest of the
poor.''
   But whether the Catholic archdiocese would support her plan was
not immediately clear.
   Archdiocese spokesman Rev. William Mendenhall said the
establishment of a Catholic hospice would have to be discussed
between Archbishop James Carney and Mother Teresa.
   ``She said she would like to care for them, but I guess the
final aspects of her motion will be between her and the
archbishop,'' said Mendenhall.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago music fans may love their football
Bears, but in Colorado, the Broncos don't seem to have the same
appeal.
   A Boulder Philharmonic Orchestra concert that was to have
featured members of the Denver Broncos football team manhandling
the baton had to be canceled after only 40 advance tickets were
sold.
   The concert, patterned after a similar event in Chicago, had
been scheduled Saturday at the University of Colorado Events Center
in Boulder.
   Billed as ``The Denver Broncos Classical Rock Concert,'' it also
was the first scheduled Boulder Philharmonic Orchestra concert to
be canceled in 32 years, said orchestra general manager Jim Hanifin.
   He thought he would have a box-office smash when he heard that
20,000 tickets were sold to watch Chicago Bears football legend
Walter Payton conduct an orchestra in Chicago.
   So he set up the concert in which the 100-member orchestra would
play hits from the Beatles, Star Wars and Bruce Springsteen in full
orchestration, with members of the NFL's American Football
Conference champions on the podium.
   Among the Broncos who had agreed to participate were Vance
Johnson, Ricky Nattiel and Mark Jackson _ known as the Three Amigos
_ and Keith Bishop and Steve Watson. Proceeds were to benefit the
Broncos Youth Foundation's efforts to combat substance abuse.
   ``I am at a total loss to understand where we messed up,''
Hanifin said. ``If Steve Watson can't draw 15,000 women, there's
something wrong.''
   Hanifin said he'll contact a Denver polling firm to conduct a
survey to find out why the show didn't attract a crowd.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HUMBOLDT, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS reporter Harry Reasoner returned to
Iowa to marry a New York health insurance executive in a private
ceremony.
   Reasoner, 65, a regular on the news show ``60 Minutes,'' married
44-year-old Lois Harriet Weber in a 25-minute ceremony Saturday
before about 30 people, mostly family, at the United Church of
Christ.
   ``I'm happy to be back, but I`m not sure when I'll be back
again,'' he said as he posed for photographers for a few minutes.
   Reasoner, dressed in a gray suit and red tie, said he and his
new wife would leave Sunday for a honeymoon in Colorado before
returning to his home in Westport, Conn. Ms. Weber wore a
calf-length pink dress.
   ``Growing up in Humboldt gave me a built-in defense against
critics who accuse major media organizations of having an East
Coast liberal bias,'' Reasoner said before the ceremony.
   A private reception was held after the wedding.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LYNNFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elizabeth Condon and Victor Novikov,
separated for more than eight years by the Soviet government, were
married on the eve of the summit between President Reagan and
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
   Condon, who teaches Russian and French in the Woburn public
schools, said, ``It's rather nice'' that the wedding Saturday
coincided with the summit in Moscow.
   Condon, 45, of Lynn and Nokikov, 56, an unemployed research
chemist from Moscow, had planned to marry in the Soviet Union in
1979, but Soviet officials blocked the wedding.
   Condon for years was denied visas to visit the Soviet Union and
Novikov was not allowed to emigrate. But the couple learned five
days before the December 1987 summit in Washington that Novikov
could come to this country. They were reunited in New York City on
March 26.
   ``They resolved us at the last one,'' she said of the 1987
summit, ``and we're sort of resolving ourselves at the beginning of
this one.''
   When Novikov arrived in the United States on a three-month visa,
he wanted to marry Condon right away. However, she wanted time to
assess their relationship. Earlier this month, Condon said, they
decided to marry.
   The two were married by a justice of the peace before 40 of
Condon's friends and relatives at the home of her aunt.
   They met two decades ago on one of Condon's then-frequent visits
to the Soviet Union.
   After a honeymoon in New York, Condon said, Novikov plans to
begin learning English and find work.
</TEXT>
