<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Summit-Notebook     05-29 0999</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Notebook,970</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Many Soviet Citizens Unfazed By Superpower Summitry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's arrival in Moscow was big news
around the world, but thousands of this city's residents seemed
oblivious to the historic occasion as they basked in the glorious
spring weather.
   As Reagan's plane touched down in the early afternoon Sunday,
the Arbat, a cobbled pedestrian walkway about a mile long, was
crowded with people strolling, watching the street artists and
standing in line to buy ice cream, shish-kabobs, sundaes, soft
drinks and juice.
   Even the military officials seemed relaxed as they sauntered
along the walkway, carrying walkie-talkies as they mingled with
pedestrians. Some sat on wooden park benches in the middle of the
walkway, which had been decorated with freshly planted flowers.
   Crowds on the walkway, lined by 16th century houses, were larger
than those gathered at the foot of the nearby street leading to
Spaso House, the home of U.S. Ambassador Jack Matlock, where Reagan
and his wife, Nancy, are staying.
   Although Soviet television broadcast the arrival and Reagan's
meeting with Mikhail S. Gorbachev live, the televisions in the
window of an electronics store showed cartoons. Another TV set in a
crowded snack bar featured a video of Tina Turner gyrating on stage
to the tune ``Get Back.''
   The Arbat is Moscow's version of Montmartre with scores of
street artists drawing portraits in charcoal and oil, where
bystanders often crowd around to watch the progression of the work;
artists line the street with their work, glow-in-the-dark oil
painters, a few restrained nudes and landscapes.
   Other forms of entertainment on the Arbat are a lone scale, with
people lined up to find out their weight and a children's show with
large stuffed farm animals _ and a live chicken. The brown bear
held a paper summit friendship flag with the stars-and-stripes and
the hammer and sickle.
   Some residents took advantage of Sunday to shop. As usual, there
were lines to purchase anything from an ice cream cone to a portion
of red sauercraut to a clump of radishes. In some stores, there are
two lines: one to pay for an item, the other to pick it up.
   One popular speciality store served two types of pate, sausage,
potato salad and sandwiches.
   And Soviets apparently aren't adverse to physical shoving when
they want to get out of a store or a jam-packed subway car.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The White House advance team handling Nancy Reagan's schedule
visited the Moscow pet market, but decided it wasn't the kind of
thing the first lady needed to see on her maiden trip to the Soviet
Union.
   The outdoor market is a fascinating slice of Soviet life: a huge
area where people sell dogs, cats, birds, fish, mice, lizards,
hamsters, snails and every kind of animal equipment from dog
brushes to aquarium cleaners.
   Held every Saturday and Sunday, the market is definitely not the
cleanest place in Moscow, nor the quietest. Debris from stalls that
have been torn down litter the area, and the dirt floor was covered
with sawdust. All the while, the animals carry on the racket of
barking, meowing and tweeting.
   The Russians carry their pets to the market all kinds of ways.
Newborn kittens peer out of gym bags or sleep in cardboard boxes,
and puppies play in playpens generally the habitat is children.
   Birds seem particularly popular. ``People buy them because they
are beautiful,'' said the man hawking his white pigeons. One
sellers stuffed at least 20 green, yellow and blue parakeets into a
cage.
   The animals, while plentiful, are not cheap. A Siamese kitten
cost about $64; a pug went for $640.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Summit-time means souvenir time, and Soviets are no different
from Americans when it comes to hawking items to commemorate the
occasion.
   The Soviets are fans of znockki, lapel pins used to decorate
outfits. Summit pins are a hit, and one of the most popular
varieties _ costing less than a dollar _ shows an American flag and
a Russian flag forming a ``V.'' ``Mockba-Moscow 1988'' is the
inscription.
   At the Hotel Mezhdunarodnaya, site of the international press
center, American-made summit tee-shirts sold like hot-cakes at $20
each. The salesgirl said she had sold about 500 in two days.
   The price didn't deter an Italian reporter who bought eight,
charging them to his American Express card. ``What are you going to
do?'' he said, explaining his family wanted the souvenirs.
   ``They won't go on sale,'' said one man from the American
Embassy, who didn't want to be quoted by name. ``There are no
specials in Russia.''
   Black sweatshirts with ``perestroikia'' on them, and white ones
with a summit designation, were on sale at the Hotel Rossiya, home
to many television journalists. They sold for 35 rubles, about $56.
   A European journalist said he ignored the price; he planned to
get a higher rate for his rubles by trading hard currency on the
black market.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The summit press center is located in a modern hotel complex
built in 1980 as an international trade complex. The facility is
much like the one the Americans set up at a hotel in Washington for
the U.S.-Soviet summit last December. It has banks of telephones
and telex printers.
   Americans and Soviets officials hold press conferences on
everything from arms control to the printing of a new book in a
cavernous room where reporters sit at long tables, many typing at
computers.
   Reporters use their press passes as collateral to get earphones
that provide simultaneous translation in English, Russian, Spanish,
French, and German.
   Soviets waiters sell cheese, salami and ham sandwiches, for a
fee, as well as instant coffee _ no milk or cream. Pepsi is
dispensed for free, but at one point it ran out.
   Tables with a range of pamphlets and books on the Soviet Union
are available for free. The White House also has a press office at
the center, while the U.S. Information Agency has its own hideaway.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
</DOC>
