<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-88 1259EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MagicPiano Bjt   05-29 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Magic Piano, Bjt,0743</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Computerized Piano Can Create `Perfect' Performance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Is it live? Or is it Bosendorfer?
   A rocket scientist and a robotics expert using a 9-foot piano
have teamed up to create an instrument that can record every
flicker of a virtuoso's finger _ and then improve on it.
   The Bosendorfer 290 SE Imperial Grand looks like a piano next to
a computer. But behind the keyboard, optical sensors, tiny electric
motors and three linked computers form the guts of a frighteningly
accurate musical instrument.
   Invented by a Wayne Stahnke, a scientist from the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration's Jet Propulsion Laboratory in
Pasadena, Calif., the Bosendorfer is played like any piano. Inside,
the instruments are recording even microscopic motions.
   Once the pianist walks away, a punch of a few computer buttons
brings forth the performance just played, depressing the piano keys
and pedals exactly as the musician did. But the Bosendorfer can
also improve on the performance.
   ``In its most straightforward mode, the piano `listens' to a
live piano performance, `remembers' that performance note for note
and then reproduces that performance _ on the very instrument upon
which that performance was played,'' said John Amuedo, a recording
engineer who worked on artificial intelligence projects at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
   The potential for the $100,000 instrument _ a sort of player
piano for the computer age _ was immediately apparent to pianist
Frederick Moyer and composer-producer Gunther Schuller, who are
collaborating on the first recording using the Bosendorfer.
   Because the piano records its own performance not with
microphones but with tiny optical and electronic sensors, the
sometimes-disturbing background noise that can crop up at a live
performance has no impact on a recording made on the Bosendorfer. A
subway car could clatter through the concert hall and it wouldn't
matter.
   Once a performance is over, the hall could be cleared and the
performance could be played amid silence. Or the piano could be
shipped to a recording studio where the keys could be punched to
bring forth the performance with all its spontaneity and energy but
none of the background noise.
   With the push of a few computer keys, the handlers of the
Bosendorfer can correct the tiniest of errors _ mistakes inaudible
to the human ear but visible among the numbers and symbols on the
computer terminal.
   ``It raises a kind of moral aesthetic question as to how perfect
you want to make your recording,'' said Schuller. ``You can make it
so perfect that it becomes almost inhuman.''
   In March, Moyer performed Mussorgsky's ``Pictures at an
Exhibition'' and several short pieces by Mendelssohn at Wellesley
College. Afterward, Schuller and Amuedo went to work on the editing
and found on the computer screen the inevitable tiny errors that
even the best of pianists make.
   Moyer's performance, the first cassette disc using the
Bosendorfer, is to be released this fall on GM Recordings.
   Amuedo defends the editing capabilities of the instrument as
merely improving techniques already widely used by recording
engineers. Record producers edit recordings heavily, even live
recordings, he argues. The Bosendorfer merely makes the process
easier and cleaner. Nor, he said, is the idea of a note-perfect
recording anything new, as anyone who has heard a player piano
knows.
   Using existing techniques, a pianist could play a passage
beautifully but make one mistake. Correcting the error would
require tossing out the well-played section and replaying it. With
the Bosendorfer, engineers merely have to plug in the correct note.
   Schuller also sees the Bosendorfer as an unparalleled teaching
tool. Pianists can listen to their own playing exactly as it sounds
on the piano. And the computer can slow down a performance without
affecting the pitch of a note, allowing pianists to judge their own
execution of rapid passages.
   Amuedo is unconcerned the Bosendorfer will kill the market for
live performances, with all their errors. A tiny mistake passes
unnoticed in a live performance, he said. On a record that is heard
several times, it can become an annoyance.
   ``No amount of editing is going to salvage a musically bad
performance,'' Amuedo said. ``When Vladimir Horowitz gets up and
plays, he makes lots and lots of mistakes and yet still people pay
$20 and $30 to hear him play because he makes music out of those
mistakes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
