<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Summit-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0774 05-29 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0774,270</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 4th graf to CORRECT call letters to BBC.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic candidate Michael Dukakis said in an
interview broadcast Sunday that the Soviet Union's economic
problems led Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev to another summit
with President Reagan.
   Dukakis, the front-runner for his party's presidential
nomination, said that Gorbachev is probably the first Soviet leader
``to recognize that Communism is a failure, at least the way it's
been practiced in the Soviet Union.''
   ``Unless the Soviet Union begins to devote significantly more
resources to its domestic economy ... and less to the military,
than they're going to become a third-rate economic power,'' he said.
   The Massachusetts governor, who was interviewed by the BBC last
week while he campaigned in California, said ``most thoughtful
observers agree that it is the very serious condition of the Soviet
domestic situation that has been largely responsible'' for
Gorbachev's involvement in the summit.
   ``I think that is the driving force behind this, the recognition
on his part that they're falling further and further behind,
they're losing the economic race, the technological race and that
they cannot be a great nation unless they significantly reduce the
amount of resources they're putting into the military,'' he said.
   Dukakis holds a commanding lead over Democratic rival Jesse
Jackson in the number of delegates needed to clinch the nomination.
And in recent opinion polls, Dukakis leads likely Republican
nominee George Bush.
   If he wins in November, Dukakis said there would be ``some very,
very significant differences'' in his foreign policy from that of
President Reagan.
   ``For one thing, I think we've got the best opportunity for
meaningful arms control and arms reduction we've had in our
lifetimes,'' he said.
