<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Summit-Demonstrations     05-29 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Demonstrations,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jews, Armenians Seek Summit Help From Reagan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About two dozen Soviet Jews waving posters and
yellow Stars of David outside the Kremlin walls urged President
Reagan on Sunday to make a summit appeal to Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev for relaxation of curbs on Jewish emigration.
   Elsewhere in the Soviet capital, Armenians beseeched Reagan to
bring up their demands for control over land in a neighboring
republic. ans also called on Reagan to bring up their demand for
control over land in a neighboring republic.
   ``We Demand Freedom of Emigration,'' read a poster held by Sasha
Ostroverkh, 7, who wore a Mickey Mouse T-shirt and was the youngest
of the Jewish protesters who gathered at the Lenin Library one
block from the Kremlin.
   Sasha's father, Vladimir, said his family has been trying to
emigrate since 1979. The government says Ostroverkh had access to
state secrets while working as a social psychologist for the
Communications Ministry.
   A few policemen kept their distance and made no attempt to
disperse the demonstrators. But workers, who normally take Sunday
off, noisily sandblasted the library steps and sprayed the
protesters and reporters with clouds of dust.
   ``A lot of refuseniks live a horrible life. Their secrets are
older than they are,'' said Ostroverkh, 42, holding up his left
hand on which he had written a prayer in Hebrew.
   He said he wanted to emigrate to Israel so ``my son can be
religious, not study things like `grandfather Lenin was good
because he made the Jews work on Sabbath.'''
   Sergei Diky, 38, who also has been refused permission to
emigrate since 1979, held a poster which read: ``We Welcome the
Summit and Hope for a Dramatic Turn in the Fate of Refuseniks.''
   ``You can only talk to my government from a firm position,'' he
said.
   ``This government is used to living not in a humane or moral
way, but in their own way,'' said Diky, whose brother and sister
emigrated to Boston in December.
   ``I hope Mr. Reagan will be strong enough not to surrender to
those who are against us,'' Ostroverkh said.
   Reagan plans to meet Monday with a group of refuseniks and
Soviet human rights activists at Spaso House, the official
residence of the U.S. ambassador where the Reagans are staying
during the five-day summit.
   Soviet authorities reportedly have made it difficult for some of
the group to see Reagan.
   According to Alexander Ogorodnikov, a Russian Orthodox activist
in Moscow, police removed two Lithuanian activists, Nijole
Sadunaite and Antanas Terleckas, from a Moscow-bound train Friday
night in their republic's capital of Vilnius.
   The following night, however, the two were told there had been a
mistake and they were allowed to travel to Moscow on Sunday for the
meeting with Reagan, Ogorodnikov said.
   Roald ``Alec'' Zelichonok, a Leningrad Jew refused permission to
emigrate for more than 10 years, said a KGB officer warned him
Thursday night he would face ``administrative measures'' if he went
to Moscow for the Reagan meeting.
   On Saturday, Ogordnikov said, police pulled five Ukrainian
Catholics off a train destined for Moscow and put on another train
headed back to Lvov. The five had hoped to meet Reagan even though
they had not been invited to Spaso House.
   Meanwhile, hundreds of Armenians gathered Sunday at
Vagankovskoye Cemetery in northwest Moscow and later at downtown
Pushkin Square ``to call on Reagan to take up our issue in his
negotiations,'' one of them said.
   Armenian painter Koryun Nahabidyan said that in their speeches
and posters, the demonstrators welcomed Reagan to the Soviet Union
and demanded that the government turn the Nagorno-Karabakh region
over to the Armenian republic.
   Nagorno-Karabakh, which is part of Azerbaijan, has been the
subject of street rallies in Moscow and the Armenian capital of
Yerevan since February.
</TEXT>
