<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-88 1423EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-VisitThatDidn'tHappen Bjt   05-29 0752</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Visit That Didn't Happen, Bjt,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities And Family Ready For Visit That Didn't Happen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan considered a private visit with a
prominent refusenik family Sunday, according to U.S. sources who
said the idea was scrubbed when word came that it could hurt the
family's chance to emigrate.
   A honey cake was baked and waiting at the apartment of Tanya,
Yuri and Vera Zieman. The Ziemans talked excitedly of how water
trucks washed their street clean and workers had daubed fresh paint
on their apartment building _ signs that the Soviets were aware of
plans for a Reagan visit.
   But the Reagans never came.
   After 11 years of waiting, it was another disappointment.
   ``When we started to apply to emigrate, I thought it would not
be easy for us,'' sighed Tanya as she gazed at the crowd on the
street. ``The one thing I didn't want to attract is publicity, the
mob, like this.''
   A U.S. official who asked not to be identified said White House
planners scrubbed consideration of a Zieman visit after the Soviets
passed word that the Ziemans would never leave the country if
Reagan went to their home.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater denied Sunday there ever
were definite plans for the Zieman visit, saying only that a number
of sites were scouted for potential Reagan trips.
   The Ziemans will be among the refuseniks, the term given to
those refused permission to emigrate, meeting with Reagan on Monday
at the Spaso House, the U.S. ambassador's home where the president
is staying.
   Human rights is one of the most contentious issues on the agenda
for Reagan's five-day Moscow summit with Kremlin leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, who has vehemently rebutted Western criticism of Soviet
human rights policies.
   Last week, the Kremlin abruptly canceled one of Monday's two
planned meetings between Reagan and Gorbachev. The discussions had
been scheduled to take place between a Reagan visit to a Moscow
monastery and his meeting with dissidents and refuseniks.
   The Ziemans are Moscow Jews who in 1977 first sought permission
to emigrate. Several other long-term refuseniks have been granted
such permission in recent months, but an estimated 2,000 Soviet
Jews have had applications pending.
   The Ziemans have been notified that they cannot leave because
Yuri, a computer specialist, would be a risk to Soviet security.
They were alerted to a possible visit by the Reagans last week,
when U.S. scouting officials came to their home.
   And they were not the only expectant parties: Soviet officials
had cleaned up the neighborhood right up to patching the road and
driveway right in front of the apartment. Local militia and
plainclothes agents patrolled the area.
   The Reagans' failure to show clearly disappointed the Ziemans
and about 300 curious residents who gathered outside their
apartment building, alerted to something unusual by the heavy
police presence.
   After the Ziemans applied to emigrate, Tanya lost her job as an
English professor and Yuri lost his as an advanced computer
specialist, working as a hospital plumber until ill health forced
him to stop last fall.
   Their elder daughter, Galya, got out of the Soviet Union last
year, apparently because authorities did not realize from her
married name of Khatutsky that she was a member of the Zieman
family. She now lives in Boston, Mass., campaigning for her
family's emigration.
   With her perfect British-accented English, curly hair and
cherubic cheeks, daughter Vera, 12, charms the many foreigners who
visit the Ziemans' three-room apartment. The presidential couple
reportedly became interested in the Ziemans' case after Vera wrote
to the Reagans in English on April 4 asking for their help to
emigrate.
   Yuri, who is suffering from hepatitis and an undiagnosed
condition that gives him double vision, lay on the sofa and
discussed his hopes for Reagan's Moscow visit.
   ``If not this visit, I don't know what will help me,'' he said.
``I think many refuseniks are expecting good news now.''
   Hopes traditionally run high amid dissidents and would-be
emigres in the Soviet Union when prominent Western politicians
visit, since the Kremlin traditionally solves several or even a few
dozen human rights cases during such meetings.
   On Sunday, very few of those who gathered on the street outside
knew the Ziemans or that they are refuseniks. They just knew
something unusual was happening.
   But one elderly lady was convinced Reagan would never show.
   ``There aren't enough security around,'' she said. ``If the
president was coming, there would be KGB in every doorway.''
</TEXT>
