<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Summit-YoungGorbachevs 1stLd-Writethru a0786 05-29 0996</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Young Gorbachevs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0786,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Roots in Provincial Russian City South of Moscow</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 16th graf, For 18, to CORRECT dialects to dialectics</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Long before they arrived in Moscow, Mikhail S.
Gorbachev and his wife Raisa were the talk of the small city where
he began his rise to power. Here, based on interviews with
acquaintances, are scenes from the lives of the young Gorbachevs.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAVROPOL, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raisa Gorbachev, professor of
Marxism-Leninism and wife of the local Communist Party chief, was
visibly piqued. For days, gossip had been spreading that she had
spent a small fortune on a fur coat.
   ``When will these rumors stop that my coat cost 12,000 rubles?''
the petite brunette from Siberia asked co-workers at the Stavropol
Agricultural Institute one day. ``It was only 608 rubles.''
   The long-ago incident, recalled by a former dean of the school
where Mrs. Gorbachev taught, could have happened today. As the wife
of the Kremlin leader, Mrs. Gorbachev has been criticized by some
Soviets who maintain she embraces Western materialism.
   It was in the provincial Russian city 850 miles south of Moscow
that Mikhail S. Gorbachev and his wife Raisa began their rise to
the top of the Kremlin hierarchy.
   The Gorbachevs lived here for 23 years, following their
graduation from Moscow State University in 1954.
   Residents remember seeing the stocky balding Gorbachev _ then
the regional party boss _ jogging some mornings along the
poplar-shaded streets or in the park opposite his one-story 19th
century home at 109 Dzherzhinksy Street.
   The couple frequented the regional art museum when it held shows
from the Hermitage, the Tretyakov or other celebrated Soviet
galleries, according to Boris A. Bendik, then museum director.
   Those who knew Gorbachev in those early years say his
flesh-pressing, street-corner brand of politicking took shape in
Stavropol, as he made his way up through the party ranks in this
city of 300,000 people set in the green, rolling hills north of the
Caucasus Mountains.
   ``He was everywhere, visiting all the stores and enterprises to
see what their problems were,'' said Tatyana I. Bessyonova, manager
of Stavropol's largest store, the Central Universal Store. ``He
listened to people's problems, and gave them advice about how to
change things.''
   The man who would make ``glasnost,'' or openness, an official
policy knew by name almost all of the journalists from
Stavropolskaya Pravda, the local party newspaper, and would often
brainstorm with them, recalled editor-in-chief Boris G. Kuchmayev.
   ``He'd come and see us and say, `Hello, fellows, what's up?'''
Kuchmayev said. ``He talked out loud about his thoughts, what he
had seen. He didn't order us to print things, but led by example.''
   One day when Gorbachev was addressing workers at the
Electoavtomatika electronics plant, the microphone failed.
   ``Other officials would have crushed bones because of that,''
said plant director Yevgeny Kuznetsov. ``Not Mikhail Sergeyevich.
He pushed aside the microphone and said, `Fine, comrades, it will
be more informal this way.'''
   For 18 years, Mrs. Gorbachev, the Siberian-born daughter of
railroad workers, taught Marxist dialectics and historical
materialism at the agricultural institute, working on the second
floor of a 19th century building where girls of good family were
once taught by Russian Orthodox priests.
   By all accounts, she was a bright, hard-working teacher who
demanded much from her students, and also from herself.
   Every year, Mrs. Gorbachev taught 180 students in the elements
of Marxism-Leninism, delivering lectures in a room with
hospital-green walls decorated with large portraits of Descartes,
Kant, Hegel and other philosophers.
   She was paid 320 rubles a month, about $500.
   Mrs. Gorbachev was once grabbed by a guard after she entered the
institute. He had mistaken her for a student, and wanted her to
leave her coat in the student's cloakroom, recalled the former
dean, Mikhail P. Chuguyev.
   ``Mikhail Pankratovich, when are people going to recognize the
fact that I work here and am not a student?'' Chuguyev recalls her
saying.
   Mrs. Gorbachev, working at a beaten wooden desk now decorated
with a single rose in a vase, taught philosophy from the ancient
Greek times to the present. Her courses were mandatory for economic
majors.
   ``She was respected greatly because she was the best prepared
... The rest of us went to her lectures to see how they should be
done,'' Chuguyev said.
   Gorbachev himself entered the institute as a part-time student
in 1962-68, working towards a degree as an ``advanced
agro-economist,'' a speciality important for someone keen on rising
in the party hierarchy in the farming region of Stavropol.
   ``He asked for no special treatment, and was interested in
pursuing the truth to the very end,'' remembers Alexander D.
Kamensky, dean of part-time students at the institute and a friend
of the Gorbachevs for decades.
   One day, in the midst of a four-hour chemistry experiment,
Gorbachev was whisked away by a limousine on urgent party business.
   But he returned later in the day, telling Kamensky, ``I want to
finish the experiment by myself and see the results.''
   Gorbachev was born in 1931 to a peasant family in Privolnoye, a
village on the black-earth steppes about 100 miles north of the
Stavropol regional center.
   With his Moscow University law diploma in his pocket, he
returned to Stavropol in 1954 as an intern in the prosecutor's
office. But he was snapped up by the Komsomol Communist youth
league, and began a career that included stints as local Komsomol
leader, party boss for the city of Stavropol and party chief for
the Stavropol region, an area about the size of South Carolina.
   When Gorbachev was named regional party chief in 1970, Raisa
Gorbachev went to her superiors at the agricultural institute, and
asked not to be named head of the philosophy department, a
promotion for which she had been in line.
   ``People will say that I've been promoted because of my
husband,'' she told her co-workers. ``Not because of what I've
done.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
