<1ST_LINE>u i AM-FreedJournalist     05-29 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Freed Journalist,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Journalist Returns Home; Report Says Italian To Be Freed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French journalist returned home to Paris on
Sunday after nine months in ``absolutely deplorable conditions'' in
an Afghan jail. A newspaper said an Italian journalist jailed in
Afghanistan would soon be freed.
   Alain Guillo was convicted on spy charges and sentenced to 10
years in prison in January. He was pardoned Friday and freed
Saturday.
   The French Communist Party newspaper L'Humanite made available a
report from its Kabul correspondent saying that Italian journalist
Fausto Biloslavo ``may be freed within two or three days.''
   The report was for Monday's edition of the newspaper.
   Guillo spent part of his detention with Biloslavo, who was
arrested in July and sentenced to seven years in prison. Guillo was
arrested in August after entering Afghanistan with guerrillas who
are fighting the Soviet-backed government.
   ``The conditions of detention were rough, absolutely
deplorable,'' Guillo, 45, told reporters at Charles de Gaulle
Airport early Sunday.
   It was ``nine months of complete isolation,'' except for rare
visits from the French charge d'affaires, he said.
   ``But it was nothing compared to the others. There is an Italian
journalist, Turkish, Iranian, Pakistani prisoners. Their life is a
real hell. They have no contact with their families. They are cut
from the world.''
   Guillo is an independent photojournalist who often worked for
the Sygma agency covering the 10-year-old civil war in Afghanistan.
   The secretary-general of the French Foreign Ministry, Gilbert
Perol, stressed that obtaining his release should not be construed
as an element of political negotiations with Afghanistan.
   Guillo's liberation was accompanied by ``no conditions, no
commitment of any sort,'' Perol said. ``We have settled the Guillo
case. Period.''
   Kabul Radio said Friday that the release followed a written
request from French President Francois Mitterrand to Afghan
President Najib and expressed hope for improved relations.
   France maintains relations with Afghanistan but has made clear
it does not support the government.
   Guillo is the sixth Frenchman jailed in Afghanistan since 1979.
In each case, a pardon was eventually granted.
   Guillo was captured August 28 while traveling with members of
the Afghan resistance on his ninth reporting trip to the country
since 1979. His arrest was announced in September.
   On Jan. 4, he was sentenced to 10 years in prison for espionage
and subversive activities.
   ``For 15 days, they (Afghan police) hesitated between killing me
on the spot and arresting me formally,'' he told reporters Saturday
in New Dehli, where he stopped en route to Paris. ``They would have
blamed the killing on the mujahedeen.''
   The Afghan rebels call themselves mujahedeen, or holy warriors.
   Guillo called his trial ``pure comedy and a travesty of
justice.''
   In a televised interview with French journalists earlier this
month, Guillo said he would never ask for a pardon because he was
not guilty and considered himself a hostage.
</TEXT>
