<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LettermanWriters     05-29 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Letterman Writers,0627</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Letterman Writers _ `Vacation' Soon Over</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For most of the members of the Writers Guild of
America, the 2{-month-old strike has been a stressful time of
picket lines, union meetings, no paychecks and lost creative
opportunity.
   For the writers of ``Late Night with David Letterman,'' being on
strike has been, well, not that different from going to work.
   ``We sleep till noon,'' said head writer Steve O'Donnell, ``get
up, drink some coffee, go down to the Writers Guild, see if
anything's going on, then we go home. But now, during the strike
....''
   Until one-liners earn them money again _ which should be soon,
since ``Late Night'' has reached a tentative independent agreement
with the guild _ the show's writers have been offering them in
magazine pieces or interviews with reporters looking for that
missed-monologue angle on the strike story. The show has been in
reruns since the strike started March 7.
   O'Donnell, joined by ``Late Night'' staffers Jeff Martin, Randy
Cohen and Maria Pope, reminisced Friday about a typical day of work
at the show.
   ``We come down to beautiful, almost-landmark Rockefeller Center
at 9:30 or 10 and linger until it's quite dark outside,'' said
O'Donnell. ``It's hand-to-mouth. We're usually working on the next
day's show, if not that day's show, the day of the broadcast. So
that's why we're not too worried about stockpiling things up.
Sometimes our days are not too miserable, because sometimes a lot
of our writing consists of a sentence. Something like ...''
   Martin: ```Let's go up and talk to our audience.'''
   ``Perfect,'' says O'Donnell. ``See, then we knock off and go get
the thickest steak in town. ... Or other times, it will just be a
phrase, a concept, a man, a plan, a canal, Panama.''
   Martin: ```Dave says something funny.'''
   O'Donnell: ```Dave takes bullhorn to window and tries to get
pedestrian to bring him up a hot dog.' Then we look at each other
and say, `That's it, that's it. Who's for dessert?'''
   But now, there are picket lines to walk.
   ``There is like just a minimum of actual union activities,''
said O'Donnell. ``We go picketing once a week.
   ``I think people passing by as they see these writers in their
not-very-solid-looking picket lines, I think they have a series of
thoughts _ the first is, do writers have a union? And then, do they
work that hard? And then perhaps the last stage is, wait a second.
TV writers get paid plenty!
   ``I don't think a lot of people understand the strike wasn't for
more money, it was to keep royalties from being cut back.''
   ``Wait a second,'' said Cohen, ``it wasn't for more money?''
   ``What the hell have we been doing?'' said Martin, who has been
playing golf.
   But seriously.
   ``We certainly support the guild,'' said O'Donnell. ``If it
wasn't for them, we'd certainly be in bad shape. But the actual
issues in this strike do not pertain to late-night comedy writers.''
   ``It's a nice little vacation,'' said Martin.
   But life on strike means missing important events in the life of
``Late Night.''
   Just that morning, the local papers were splashed with
Letterman's smiling file-photo face next to headlines about a
``mystery woman'' driving his car who told officials at the Lincoln
Tunnel, where she didn't have the toll, that she was ``Mrs. David
Letterman.''
   ``Usually Dave has to go on a murder spree to make the front
page of the New York Post,'' said Martin. And he recommends, ``if
you're going to steal Dave's car, please, please have correct
change.''
</TEXT>
