<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Refuseniks     05-29 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Refuseniks,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Jews Demand That U.S. Link Deals To Jewish Emigration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Jewish activists urged President Reagan
on Sunday to drive a hard bargain for free Jewish emigration when
he meets with Mikhail S. Gorbachev in Moscow.
   ``The Soviets will not be persuaded by mere words,'' Yuli
Edelstein, a former Soviet labor camp inmate, said during a rally
for Soviet Jews attended by about 200 people in Jerusalem.
   Edelstein and other activists demanded that the United States
link trade agreements and scientific and cultural exchanges to the
level of Jewish emigration from the Soviet Union.
   The activists also described Gorbachev's policy of ``glasnost,''
or openness, as a public relations stunt that has not led to real
improvements for Soviet Jews.
   ``More than 2 million Jews remain in one big labor camp _ the
Soviet Union _and the door is still closed,'' said Moshe Arens, a
member of Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's Cabinet and the
right-wing Likud bloc.
   Arens called on Reagan to use the level of Jewish emigration as
a test for Soviet sincerity on other issues, such as arms control.
   Shamir aide Avi Pazner said in a telephone interview that ``we
have seen very few (Soviet) changes,'' but added that Shamir was
satisfied with Reagan's efforts.
   U.S. officials have said the plight of Soviet Jewry would be on
the summit agenda. Reagan was to meet Monday with a group of
prominent ``refuseniks,'' Soviet Jews denied permission to emigrate.
   Refusenik Zeev Dashevsky told Israel army radio in a telephone
interview from Moscow that he viewed his scheduled meeting with
Reagan as a sign that the president assigned importance to the
issue.
   ``We want to tell him that even though positive things have been
done in the past two years, basic problems remain and the situation
is not good at all,'' said Dashevsky, who has been denied an exit
visa for the past 11 years.
   Moscow has released several prominent Jewish activists from
prisons and labor camps in the past year. Last year, 8,011 Jews
left the Soviet Union, the highest number since 1981.
   The Soviet Union severed ties with Israel after the 1967 Middle
East war during which Israel captured territory from Moscow's Arab
allies.
   In the past year, the Soviets sent a consular delegation to
Jerusalem, and approved a reciprocal visit by Israeli diplomats.
</TEXT>
