<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Politics     05-29 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hawks Warn Labor Party Risking Elections By Veering Left</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some politicians in Foreign Minister Shimon
Peres' left-leaning Labor Party fear that a newly chosen slate of
dovish candidates could cost them the national elections in
November.
   Their concern was triggered by a meeting of the party's Central
Committee on Thursday in which more than half of 29 candidates
chosen to run for parliament favor making more concessions to the
Arabs for peace than the party has advocated in the past.
   The party's dovish turn appears to contradict a recent shift in
Israeli public opinion polls, which show a majority support
right-wing Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and his allies in
espousing a tougher stand toward the Arabs.
   ``I am definitely worried by the change. The fact is, more doves
than expected were elected, and this will harm us very much in the
elections,'' Agriculture Minister Aryeh Nehamkin said.
   Those on Labor's new slate include several peace activists and a
former ultra left-wing legislator, Lova Eliav, who has had contacts
with the PLO and has advocated a full Israeli pullout from the West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The latest public opinion poll, taken this month and published
May 13 by the Yediot Ahronot daily, showed Labor and allied parties
winning 59 seats. The Likud and its allies were predicted to win 61.
   After Israel's last elections, in 1984, the Labor and Likud
parties formed a coalition in which Labor's Peres served as prime
minister for the first two years and Likud's Shamir for the past
two years.
   Political analysts say Israelis' swing to the right reflects a
hawkish public mood stirred by the six-month-old Palestinian
uprising in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The analysts say that the Labor infighting could further damage
the party's electoral image by presenting a confused picture to the
public.
   ``With such a fractious and contradictory slate it will be
difficult to formulate an attention-grabbing campaign to compete
with parties either to the left or the right,'' wrote columnist Dan
Margalit in the Haaretz daily.
   The doves and hawks in the Labor Party are divided over how to
implement a plank in its platform which calls for giving up some
land occupied in the 1967 Middle East War in exchange for peace
with Arab states.
   The hawks favor a formula which would leave Israel with the
Jordan River Valley, a stand unacceptable to Arabs. They also
completely reject negotiations with the PLO.
   Labor's newest candidates have a more lenient approach to
territorial compromise and some favor talking with the PLO if it
officially recognizes Israel.
   ``I think that Labor is back where it should be, on the road of
looking for peace, that peace has a price and you don't get it
without compromising,'' said Russian-born Lova Eliav, 66.
   He predicted a tough Israeli election campaign over the peace
issue.
   ``People are extreme, dangerously so. I think it's time for
voters to choose a party that wants to take the road for peace,
even if it's a very, very uphill road,'' he said.
</TEXT>
