<1ST_LINE>r p AM-MaineCongressional     05-29 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Maine Congressional,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>L.L. Bean heiress, Party Insider Seek GOP Congressional Nomination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEN O'QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The heiress to Maine's most famous modern
fortune and one of the Republican establishment's favorite sons are
vying for the GOP nomination to challenge Democratic incumbent
Joseph E. Brennan, a former governor, for his House seat.
   On June 14, Republican voters in Maine's 1st Congressional
District will choose between businesswoman Linda Bean-Jones, a
granddaughter of L.L. Bean, and Edward S. ``Ted'' O'Meara, the
executive assistant to the state's popular senior senator, William
S. Cohen. Both candidates are making their first bid for public
office.
   With a campaign fund 10 times the size of O'Meara's, Bean-Jones
is far better financed, partly because she has loaned her campaign
$168,000. Much of that war chest has been spent on television
advertising, which emphasizes her links to the sporting goods
empire founded by her grandfather and plays down her background as
a conservative publisher and activist.
   ``I'm prepared to spend whatever it takes to win,'' she said.
   O'Meara is little known outside GOP inner circles and is
counting on support from Republican regulars to win next month's
primary. But he has been hampered by a tradition of neutrality in
primary campaigns, which has limited the activities of some of his
natural allies, including Gov. John R. McKernan, U.S. Rep. Olympia
J. Snowe and even Cohen himself.
   Publicly, however, O'Meara is undaunted.
   ``Never once did I ask them for an endorsement,'' O'Meara said.
``I never had any expectation of it. I never wanted to put them in
the position of having to get involved in the primary.''
   The GOP primary winner will face Brennan, a former two-term
governor, in November's general election for his 1st District seat,
which represents 563,073 residents in an area about the size of
Connecticut. Brennan, who was elected to the House in 1986 as he
concluded eight years as governor, is unopposed for the Democratic
nomination.
   Also unopposed in the primary is Snowe, who is winding up her
fifth term as the 2nd District incumbent. The Democrats have lined
up former state Sen. Kenneth Hayes, who teaches at the University
of Maine in Orono, to challenge her in the general election.
   Bean-Jones, 46, is perhaps best known as founder of the
ultraconservative Maine Paper, a weekly publication which folded in
1982 after three years.
   She also played a role in the successful campaign to defeat an
Equal Rights Amendment to the state constitution, and traveled to
an arms control meeting in Geneva to support President Reagan's
Strategic Defense Initiative.
   Her focus on issues has changed since announcing her candidacy.
Now she refers to herself as ``the private sector candidate'' who
wants to eliminate many small-business regulations. She is against
higher taxes and abortion, but favors helping women on welfare find
jobs by providing day care, and she said she approves the expanded
use of nuclear power.
   Since becoming a candidate she also has adopted her family
surname, saying, ``I cherish the connection. It embodies what I am
today.''
   O'Meara, 36, is a seasoned organizer, having worked on several
gubernatorial and congressional campaigns. He was an aide to Snowe
before taking a position in 1981 with Cohen, for whom he has served
as campaign finance director. He now is in charge of the senator's
six offices in Maine.
   O'Meara said he favors reductions in the federal deficit, is
pro-choice on abortion, favors the Equal Rights Amendment and wants
action, not further study, to curb acid rain pollution.
</TEXT>
