<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Summit-SovietMedia 1stLd-Writethru a0778thatabout30minutesafterthekTurnaround'onEast-WestRelations
05-29 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Soviet Media, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0778,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Press Sees Reagan `Turnaround' on East-West Relations</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts 5 grafs after 3rd graf bgng: Soviet television ... to
UPDATE with Soviet TV coverage on Vremya, Adds byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN FRIEDMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet press said Sunday that President Reagan
had made a ``turnaround'' on East-West relations in the past three
years, resulting from a fresh look at changing world realities
rather than a reversal of his staunch anti-communist views.
   One commentator said the Soviet Union has high hopes for
Reagan's fourth summit meeting with Mikhail S. Gorbachev, but
another said progress will depend largely on whether Reagan's
approach is ``realistic and constructive.''
   Soviet television pre-empted regular programming for a live
broadcast of the president's arrival at Moscow's Vnukovo Airport
and his initial meeting with the Soviet leader in St. George's Hall
in the Kremlin.
   An expanded, 90-minute version of the evening news program
``Vremya'' devoted a full 52 minutes to the summit, rerunning much
of the welcoming ceremony at the airport and the speeches by both
leaders. It also carried more than two minutes on Nancy Reagan's
tour of the Cathedral of the Assumption conducted by Raisa
Gorbachev, giving rare prominence to the wife of a Soviet leader.
   ``Vremya'' carried a lengthy interview with Gorbachev adviser
Georgi Arbatov, a member of the Soviet Communist Party Central
Committee and director of the Institute of U.S.A. and Canada. He
dismissed past anti-Soviet speeches by Reagan as ``propaganda.''
   ``I didn`t see in them any serious political topics,'' Arbatov
said. ``It was what is called in America `public relations,' and in
many cases, of course, unconvincing propaganda.''
   ``Vremya'' also took to the streets for public opinion on the
summit. Many people spoke of hopes for peace and lessening the
nuclear threat, although one man scolded the United States for
raising human rights issues.
   ``They should report on their own human rights problems before
discussing ours,'' the unidentified man told the ``Vremya''
interviewer.
   State-run newspapers printed traffic restrictions that will be
in effect until Reagan leaves the Soviet capital on Thursday.
   The Communist Party newspaper Pravda printed Reagan's official
portrait and biography in the bottom right corner of its front
page, as is customary for visiting heads of state.
   Tass, the official news agency, said that ``the biographies of a
son of a shoe dealer from Illinois and a son of a peasant from the
Stavropol region represent ... the essence of the two opposite ways
of life.''
   Said Tass: ``This is going to be a meeting of two fundamentally
different social systems with their own values, ideals and
priorities. The relations between them determine to a large extent
the fate of the whole planet.''
   In a separate dispatch, Tass diplomatic correspondent Vadim
Biryukov wrote:
   ``Just three years ago, there was hardly anyone who could
imagine that the 40th American president, known for his
anti-Communist views and power approaches to the solution of
problems on the international scene, would be the high
representative of the United States that would sign a Soviet-U.S.
intermediate-range nuclear forces treaty and moreover, bring to the
Soviet capital the first document on nuclear arms reduction in
history, ratified by the U.S. Senate.''
   ``Does it mean that the American leader has changed his views?''
Biryukov asked.
   ``Perhaps it would be more correct to describe this turnaround
as a result of understanding the fact that the world has changed
and that the interests of our countries are changing. And the
president has probably taken a fresh look at the existing realities
without giving up his known views.''
   Biryukov said the Soviet Union ``pins its most serious hopes''
on the summit meeting.
   Pravda said summit progress depends largely on ``how realistic
and constructive'' is Reagan's approach.
   Biryukov wrote that since the December summit talks in
Washington, the United States has not allowed any progress toward
agreement on the Reagan's Star Wars plan for a space-based shield
against nuclear attack. The Soviets regard the Strategic Defense
Initiative as a violation of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
</TEXT>
