<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Pool     05-29 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Pool,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Powerful Ship Gives Commanders Many Options, Says Skipper</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: This story was filed through the Pentagon media pool in the
Persian Gulf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD USS VINCENNES IN THE PERSIAN GULF (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of
this super-sophisticated warship says its presence in the Persian
Gulf gives U.S. officials many new options, including reducing the
number of Navy vessels.
   ``I think that it really gives the tactical commanders here in
the gulf an opportunity to pick and choose as they see fit,'' Capt.
Will C. Rogers III said in an interview on the bridge of the
9,400-ton Vincennes.
   The Vincennes on was on its first trip north through the gulf.
   Its arrival in the waterway was part of an extensive turnover in
the Navy's gulf-based force planned for the next several days. At
least 10 ships are involved in the rotation, announced by the
Pentagon in April.
   The San Diego-based Vincennes is the first of the Navy's
billion-dollar Aegis missile cruisers to be deployed as a member of
the Middle East Force operating in the gulf.
   The Aegis system is an array of powerful radars and missile
weaponry linked with computers to enable a single ship to manage a
widespread battle, carrying out dozens of radar surveillance and
firing missions at the same time.
   U.S. officials have not explained why the Vincennes, designed
primarily for carrier battle group defense in the open ocean, is
being assigned to the gulf, where its long reach and massive clout
would appear to exceed any current threat posed to the Navy's
convoy escort operations or U.S. interests.
   Some Vincennes officers and crew members say privately they are
puzzled by the deployment. The ship was abruptly pulled out of a
naval exercise off California. After less than four days in port to
prepare, it made a 13,000-mile high-speed dash to the Arabian Sea
in 32 days.
   The Vincennes' varied capabilities can make it the equivalent of
several other warships in a combat situation, Rogers said Saturday.
   ``It can be a force multiplier. On the other side of the coin,
because of these capabilities, to manage an area as large as the
Persian Gulf, virtually as far as its surveillance capabilities, it
can be a force reducer as well,'' he said.
   Asked whether the Navy was considering a cut in the 17 warships
it has in the gulf, Rogers said that was ``above my pay grade, but
there certainly is an option there.''
   Iran and Iraq both have attacked neutral ships during the
``tanker war,'' a four-year spinoff of their 7{-year gulf war. More
than 500 commercial vessels have been damaged, several have been
sunk and more than 300 seamen have died during the tanker war.
   Rogers, who earlier described Iran as a ``low-level threat'' in
the gulf, said the armed speedboats used by Iran to raid neutral
shipping, usually in reprisal for Iraqi air attacks, cannot be
disregarded.
   ``Small craft are always difficult targets, and a dedicated
attack by anyone who wants to press it home is a difficult problem
to deal with, regardless of the capabilities of the defender,'' he
said.
   Rogers said his ship would stay alert, but ``at the same time I
don't want to give the impression that we're leaning forward on our
toes to get a major conflagration started here, because that's not
the case at all.''
   U.S. policy in the gulf recently was expanded to allow Navy
ships to intervene in attacks on vessels not flying the U.S. flag.
Iran has carried out four such raids since then, but U.S. officials
say no American warships were close enough to get involved.
   Rogers, a native of Fort Worth, Texas, said the Vincennes,
despite its high-tech radar and weapons, is as vulnerable as other
warships to mines, ``and that basically is where our prime concern
is.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
