<DOCNO> AP880529-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-88 1659EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Co-edSchools     05-29 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Co-ed Schools,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>St. Bernard High Schools Going Co-Ed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHALMETTE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The valedictorian at St. Bernard High
School was a bit wistful at last week's graduation as he recalled
some of the problems his class faced at one of the parish's
single-sex secondary schools.
   During freshman year, the boys in his class had to cope with
intimidation from upperclassmen, Joseph Zanco said.
   ``In our sophomore year, we had another problem to deal with _
females. They were everywhere but in the school,'' he said.
   Zanco's successor will be spared that lament because next year
the four high schools in St. Bernard Parish in suburban New Orleans
will go co-educational for the first time in a generation.
   The change was sparked by a lawsuit won last year by a parent
last year who wanted his son and daughter to attend the same school.
   Hilbert Wall's suit said his children were victims of
discrimination because they weren't being taught the same things.
Calls to Wall's home went unanswered Sunday.
   Court-ordered racial desegregation of New Orleans schools helped
lead to the sexual segregation of St. Bernard's high schools 22
years ago.
   The parish was a magnet for so-called ``white flight'' from the
inner city, and the population boom strapped the school board's
budget. To economize, school officials decided to split high
schools by sex, building sports stadiums at boys' schools and home
economics labs at girls schools.
   ``At the time, we thought we were doing the taxpayers a
service,'' Davies said. ``It all went off quite well. In those
days, there weren't many boys trying to be cheerleaders. And being
a secretary was still thought of as a job for girls. So there was
no reason to have a big stenographic lab for boys _ they just
weren't going to sign up for it.''
   School Board President John Lane said the reversion to
co-education won't be cheap. A no-frills conversion _ modifying
bathrooms, adding extra equipment and duplicating courses _ will
cost the board about $300,000, he said.
   ``Financially, it's going to be devastating this year,'' Lane
said. ``But the staff is ready. And the kids are ready.''
   Henry Smith, a supervisor with St. Bernard Parish schools,
looked forward to the change. ``It teaches kids to socialize
better. And it's my personal observation that students tend to
behave a bit better,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
