<HEAD>Dukakis Woos Environmental Support In New Jersey; Prepares For
Meetings With Black Supporters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELMAR, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential front-runner Michael
Dukakis wooed environmentalists Sunday while campaigning in advance
of New Jersey's primary and prepared to meet with black supporters
to plot a national strategy for the fall.
   The Massachusetts governor, apparently confident of a win here
June 7, made only two public appearances, taking a boat cruise with
environmentalists before heading to a barbecue.
   As the S.S. Miss Belmar prepared to head out into polluted ocean
waters, Dukakis told a small gathering at the docks that as
president he would forcefully direct cleanup programs.
   ``I'm going to do everything I can as president of the United
States ... to make sure that our oceans and our rivers and our
coastlines are what they ought to be,'' Dukakis said.
   He said a strong federal environmental policy is particularly
needed in areas like New Jersey, which blames much of the pollution
in its waters on neighboring New York.
   Ironically, the Reagan administration appointee who heads the
Boston EPA office had to get a court order to speed up the Dukakis'
administration's cleanup of Boston Harbor, the nation's filthiest
harbor.
   ``Nobody is without sin,'' Dukakis said, conceding he was wrong
to delay the cleanup, which will cost more than $3 billion.
   While aboard the boat, members of local environmental groups
showed Dukakis a harbor chart marked in areas polluted by sewage,
sludge and trash dumping. Less than a mile off one public beach a
brown film covered the water, which was strewn with floating
garbage.
   ``It's pretty disgusting,'' Dukakis said.
   Dukakis denounced the dumping of raw sewage into waterways and
said the nation's trash-disposal problem could be eased with vastly
expanded recycling and conservation programs. He also spoke in
favor of new, biodegradeable plastics made from corn and other
crops.
   Dukakis, who hopes to lock up the Democratic nomination with
wins in New Jersey and California on the final primary day, also
attended three private receptions, a gathering with Hispanic
leaders, an environmental forum and a reception for a state senator
running for Congress.
   He was to return home to Boston Sunday night and meet Monday
morning with about 60 black supporters from across the country
before attending local Memorial Day services..
   Dukakis has conceded the black vote to rival Democrat Jesse
Jackson throughout the primary season. In recent weeks, however, he
has begun to actively seek black support, which is seen a critical
in order to defeat the expected GOP candidate, Vice President
George Bush _ particularly in closely contested Southern states.
   Jackson also was in New Jersey on Sunday, while Bush was
conducting private meetings with advisers at his summer home in
Maine.
   Polls have shown Dukakis with a wide lead over Jackson here.
   Dukakis was to return to New Jersey later this week before
heading back to California to campaign through primary day. He also
plans to make stops in Montana and New Mexico, which also hold June
7 primaries.
</TEXT>
