<HEAD>Party Leaders of Azerbaijan, Armenia Meet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new Communist Party leaders of the southern
republics of Azerbaijan and Armenia met Sunday and discussed ways
to lessen the tension between their ethnic groups, the Tass news
agency reported.
   Tass said Abdul-Rahman Vezirov of Azerbaijan and Suren
Arutyunyan of Armenia, who were selected to their posts May 21,
visited factories in both republics.
   ``They examined the issues of stepping up economic and cultural
relations and educating working people in a spirit of
internationalism,'' Tass said.
   Internationalism is a Soviet buzzword for tolerance of other
ethnic groups, and the Tass reference indicated that the two
leaders discussed the tense relations that earlier this year
erupted into violence in which at least 32 people were killed.
   Armenians are demanding that Nagorno-Karabakh, an area of
Azerbaijan whose population is predominantly ethnic Armenian, be
annexed to Armenia.
   Hundreds of thousands of people demonstrated in the streets of
the Armenian capital of Yerevan in mid-February. Three days of
rioting broke out at the end of February in the Azerbaijani city of
Sumgait. Officials said 26 Armenians and six Azerbaijanis were
killed.
   Unrest began to rise again in recent weeks, and on May 21 top
Communist Party officials held meetings in both Armenia and
Azerbaijan. Armenian party leader Karen Demirchyan and Azerbaijani
leader Kyamran Bagirov were fired.
   Vezirov was the Soviet ambassador to Pakistan, while Arutyunyan
had been Armenia's first deputy prime minister.
