<2ND_LINE>AM-Raisa-Time,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet First Lady Sends Wishes to American Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raisa Gorbachev wishes American women and their
families ``peaceful and clear skies over our planet'' in a message
the Soviet first lady sent to Time magazine.
   ``The more we learn about the life of the peoples of our
countries today, their concerns and their aspirations, the sooner
we will have a better understanding of one another,'' Mrs.
Gorbachev wrote.
   The magazine said Mrs. Gorbachev sent the unsolicited message
after learning that Time was preparing an article on contemporary
Soviet women.
   ``I retain warm memories of the meetings I had with American
women in Moscow and Washington in December 1987,'' Mrs. Gorbachev
said. ``Quite a number of differences stand between us. But I feel
that they in no way hinder discussions of any problems that are of
concern to us: how to preserve peace, how to make the life of every
individual on Earth worthy of our times.''
   The letter went on to describe Soviet women's contributions to
the history of their country, ``marked by striking selflessness and
self-sacrifice, by boundless kindness and charity.''
   ``Our women know the price of war and peace. They are ardent and
convinced champions of peace,'' Mrs. Gorbachev wrote.
   ``Today the Soviet woman is proud of her participation in
`perestroika,' in the renewal of society. There are grounds for
this. Perestroika is distinguished by a vigorous social policy.
This is very important for improving people's everyday life and
family life and for the upbringing of children.''
   The letter concludes: ``I sincerely wish the readers of Time,
all American women and their families peaceful and clear skies over
our planet, and happiness.''
</TEXT>
