<HEAD>Baker: Meese Could Hurt Bush's Presidential Prospects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House chief of staff Howard Baker said
Sunday that President Reagan still has confidence in Attorney
General Edwin Meese III but believes Meese's legal problems could
harm George Bush politically.
   Baker said Reagan ``certainly doesn't have a closed mind'' about
Meese, but the chief of staff added: ``It would take an
extraordinary event to shake that confidence that the president
still has in the attorney general.''
   Baker, interviewed on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' was questioned
about reports that Vice President Bush would like to see Meese
leave the Justice Department, and said that while Bush's opinions
carry weight in the administration, ``the president must decide
these issues himself.''
   Baker acknowledged Meese's problems could hurt Bush's election
prospects, but added that ``the show isn't over yet,'' noting that
independent counsel James McKay has yet to report the results of
his investigation of the attorney general's financial dealings.
   ``Let's give Meese his opportunity to rebut whatever
allegations, if any, are made in the McKay report before we make a
final judgement on its ultimate political impact,'' Baker said.
   Asked if Reagan shares Baker's judgement that Meese's woes could
hurt Bush politically, Baker said: ``Oh, I think so _ for the
moment and to some degree. But I think that he too would urge you
to wait and see how all this unfolds and develops.''
