<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia-Kidnap 1stLeadWritethru   05-29 0801</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Kidnap, 1st Lead Writethru,a0823,0829</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Presidential Candidate Kidnapped</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with bodyguard dying, president
ordering search, details on kidnapping, another ambush, CORRECTS
day of guerrilla action to Saturda, CORRECTS guerrilla group that
attacked pipeline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Men firing submachine guns kidnapped a
newspaper executive and former Conservative presidential candidate
Sunday and killed his bodyguard.
   Alvaro Gomez Hurtado, 69, the son of former President Laureano
Gomez, was seized as he left church.
   The abduction came during a wave of leftist guerrilla violence,
including the kidnapping of three mayors-elect of small towns, two
ambushes that left seven soldiers dead, and guerrilla attacks on
two towns and an oil pipeline.
   Gomez's family issued a statement confirming the kidnapping.
Some radio stations reported the family said Gomez had been
wounded, but the statement did not say that. The statement appealed
for medical attention for Gomez in case he had been wounded.
   An anonymous person claiming to be one of the kidnappers called
the Bogota radio station Todelar. Then a voice sounding like Gomez
said in Spanish, ``Oh, oh, I'm dying.''
   Todelar played a recording of the telephone call.
   President Virgilio Barco, on a state visit to Portugal, said in
a statement that he ordered all government security forces to
search for Gomez.
   Gomez was leaving the church across from the British Embassy on
a broad, tree-lined street in the northern part of the Colombian
capital when the kidnappers jumped him.
   ``I had said goodbye (to Gomez) and had walked maybe 15 steps
when I heard the sound of submachine guns,'' said a former federal
senator, Alfonso Palacio.
   ``I hit the ground and then I saw four men pushing him into a
car,'' Palacio said in an interview with radio station RCN.
   Gomez's only bodyguard was hit by 14 bullets and died in a
hospital, police said.
   There was no claim of responsibility for the abduction of Gomez,
director of the Bogota morning daily El Siglo. In editorials, Gomez
has consistently called for ``a country free of guerrillas.''
   Leftist guerrillas, right-wing death squads, drug traffickers
and other criminals all have been active in kidnapping and killing
public officials in the last five years.
   Gomez last ran for president on the Conservative party ticket in
March 1986 and was defeated by Barco, the Liberal Party candidate.
   Gomez' son, Mauricio Gomez, who was the director of a television
news program, fled to Madrid last year after he received kidnapping
threats. He is still living in Madrid.
   An army colonel, a captain and three other soldiers were killed
in an apparent guerrilla ambush Sunday near San Vicente in the
northern state of Santander, the police said in a communique.
   A lieutenant and a soldier were killed in another ambush in the
northern region of Urba, RCN quoted the national police as saying.
   The mayors-elect were kidnapped Saturday in towns in the
northern state of Bolivar. They are Andres Castro of Pinillos,
Antonio Morato of Rio Viejo and Henry Cosio of Barrnaco de Loba,
the police said.
   A leftist guerrilla group, the National Liberation Army, claimed
responsibililty, police said. The mayors-elect were to have taken
office next Wednesday.
   Two months ago 16 mayors were kidnapped by leftist guerrillas
who lectured the mayors to do more for the poor and then let them
go.
   Leftist guerrillas Saturday attacked Carcasi, 220 miles
northeast of Bogota, and Majugual, 280 miles north of Bogota, the
police said.
   Guerrillas firing mortars, rocket propelled grenades and
automatic assault rifles stormed the police station in Carcasi, a
statement from the national police said.
   Two policemen were killed, three were wounded and three were
captured, and the police station was reduced to rubble, the
statement said.
   The guerrillas left pamphlets saying they were members of the
National Liberation Army, which follows the communist ideology of
Cuban president Fidel Castro.
   Another guerrilla group, the Maoist People's Liberation Army,
attacked the police station in Majugual and tried unsuccessfully to
rob the town's only bank, but the police repulsed the attackers,
the statement said.
   The National Liberation Army blew up the country's main oil
pipeline again Saturday, another police statement said.
   The pipeline takes oil from the big Canon Limon field on the
Venezuelan border in the northeast state of Arauca. Occidental
Petrolem, Royal Dutch Shell and the Colombian state oil company,
Ecopetrol, operate the field.
   Several yards of the pipeline were destroyed in the explosion
and thousands of gallons of oil were spilled before pumps could be
shut down, police said.
   The 500-mile pipeline goes to Covenas, a port on Colombia's
Caribbean coast.
   It was the 26th time this year that the guerrilla group has
attacked the pipeline. The group says it will continue the attacks
until foreign oil companies' operations in Colombia are
nationalized.
</TEXT>
