<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cyprus     05-29 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cyprus,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turkish Cypriots Burn Effigy of U.N. Commander After Fatal
Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 600 Turkish Cypriots rallied Sunday
to demand the removal of the Austrian commander of the U.N.
peacekeeping force on the divided island after a U.N. soldier
killed a Turkish Cypriot.
   Protesters burned an effigy of Maj. Gen. Gunther Greindl, the
commander of the 2,300-man U.N. force, and carried banners calling
him a murderer.
   The rally followed a religious service in a mosque in Famagusta
in memory of Hussein Kafa. The 57-year-old farmer was killed May 21
in the village of Pyla, the only place where the Turkish Cypriots
and Greek Cypriots still live together.
   Officials of the U.N. force said Kafa crossed into the
peacekeeping force's zone of operations in the village, claiming he
wanted to mend a wall around his farm.
   They said that when two Austrian soldiers ordered him out of the
buffer zone, he drew a pistol and fired at them. The soldiers fired
back three pistol shots, killing Kafa instantly.
   Rauf Denktash, president of the breakaway Turkish Cypriot state
in the northern third of the island, charged after the shooting
that Greindl ordered Austrian troops to harass Kafa and held him
responsible. Greindl denied the allegation.
   At the end of the rally, Kafa's three daughters left a black
wreath at the Austrian base.
   The eastern Mediterranean island has been divided into Greek and
Turkish sectors since 1974, when Turkey invaded the island in the
wake of an Athens-backed coup.
   In another development, Kenan Atakol, head of the foreign and
defense ministeries of the self-proclaimed Turkish state, accused
the peacekeepers of negligence in the shooting death of a Turkish
soldier by Greek Cypriot police on Saturday.
   Cpl. Yusuf Sanli was shot after he tried to rape a Greek Cypriot
woman, fatally shot a national guardsman and wounded another,
officials in the southern Greek sector said.
   ``The village where the killing took place is in the buffer
zone, which should be under the control of the U.N. force,'' Atakol
said at a news conference. ``They should not have let the armed
Greek Cypriots enter this region.''
   About 30,000 Turkish soldiers are based in the Turkish sector.
The village, Atheniou, is near the green line that divides the
sectors.
   Greek Cypriot police moved into the village southeast of Nicosia
several hours after the guardsmen were shot and fatally shot the
soldier when he tried to open fire at them.
   ``There is negligence on the part of the peacekeeping forces,''
Atakol said. ``Had they informed us before the operation launched,
death of the two soldiers would have been avoided.''
   He said Sanli might have crossed the line by mistake and tried
to hide or ask for food. ``My investigation shows that he was a
good-mannered, disciplined and religious person,'' he said.
</TEXT>
