<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Massacre     05-29 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Massacre,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Historian Predicts Probe Will Blame Soviets For World War II
Massacre</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dissident historian predicted Sunday that a
joint Soviet-Polish investigation will determine that Soviet, not
Nazi German forces, were responsible for a World War II massacre of
thousands of Polish soldiers.
   ``I think the new commission will determine we are to blame,''
Roy A. Medvedyev said in a telephone interview.
   The Soviet government has for years blamed the killing of more
than 4,000 Polish officers in the Katyn Forest on Nazi occupation
forces. But on May 11, the Soviet newspaper Literary Gazette
published the first hint that Moscow would accept the version of
Western historians.
   Western scholars say the massacre in the forest near Smolensk,
250 miles west of Moscow, was carried out in April 1940 by the NKVD
_ the Soviet state security and police force headed then by
Lavrenti Beria, the dreaded henchman of dictator Josef V. Stalin.
   ``I have seen German protocols which said that Soviet bullets
were found in the exhumed bodies,'' the Literary Gazette quoted
Soviet historian A. Latshev as saying at a Moscow symposium of
Polish and Soviet historians and filmmakers.
   Latshev said the ``blank spot'' of the Katyn massacre could no
longer be tolerated.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, under his policy of
glasnost, or openness, has encouraged historians to uncover the
truth about historical events that were formerly distorted or
banned from discussion. The policy has led to sensational
admissions of repressions under Stalin.
   Last year, Gorbachev and Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski
signed an agreement on ideological cooperation that stressed the
necessity for a more truthful history of Polish-Soviet relations. A
Soviet-Polish commission was set up to investigate ``blank spots''
in the two countries' relations.
   Radio Moscow, in a report Thursday monitored by the British
Broadcasting Corp. in London, said a wreath-laying ceremony was
held at a recently renovated monument at Katyn to ``the Polish
officers shot dead by the Nazis in 1941.'' But the report went on
to say that version of the massacre was now being reconsidered.
   Relatives and families of the executed Polish officers will,
under new rules, be allowed to visit the memorial, the broadcast
quoted Smolensk regional official Alexei Orlov as saying.
   In 1944, a Soviet commission stated that the officers were
killed by Germans, but in the early 1950s, a U.S. investigatory
commission blamed the Soviets.
   Mevedyev said times have changed and that ``the Poles insist on
an objective investigation.'' He predicted the result will be a
finding that Stalin and Beria were responsible.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
