<2ND_LINE>AM-Stunt Crash,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilot Killed in Air Show Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stunt pilot was killed before thousands
of people at an airshow Sunday when his biplane crashed and skidded
into a lake, authorities said.
   The plane crashed at Mountain Shadows Lake at 10:45 a.m. after
the pilot failed to steer out of a dive, authorities said.
   The pilot's body was recovered from the lake shortly after noon,
said Bob Newman, a trooper with the Texas Department of Public
Safety. His name was withheld ending notification of relatives,
Newman added.
   The plane hit the ground 250 feet from the banks of the private,
man-made lake about 15 miles east of El Paso, where thousands had
gathered for a Memorial Day weekend air show and hot air balloon
festival, Newman said.
   ``He had just completed doing a loop and he came out of the loop
headed west, but he took it too low,'' Newman said. ``He hit the
ground and skidded ... about 11 feet into the lake and sank in 18
feet of water.''
   Terry Martin, a spokesman for the Federal Aviation
Administration, gave no immediate details of the crash.
