<2ND_LINE>AM-Toddler Fall,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toddler Survives 100-Foot Balcony Plunge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARCO ISLAND, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bushy trees and soft earth helped a
17-month-old boy survive a more than 100-foot plunge from the
10th-floor balcony of an oceanfront hotel, authorities said.
   Ryan C. Lee of East Falmouth, Mass., apparently slipped through
a balcony railing at the Marriott Marco Island Resort on Friday
afternoon and hurtled 85 feet before smacking into a bushy sabal
palm.
   He broke through the branches of another tree before landing
headfirst in soft dirt.
   ``I'd say he's real lucky,'' Collier County sheriff's Sgt. John
McGuire said. ``If that had been me, I would have died on the way
down _ of fright.''
   The child was in satisfactory condition at Naples Community
Hospital Sunday night. He suffered a bump on the back of his head,
a black eye and a scratch on his stomach, a sheriff's report said.
   A hospital nursing supervisor declined to give further details.
   Ryan's parents, Paul Lee, 34, a physician, and Sharon Lee, 30,
checked into the hotel about 30 minutes before the accident.
Deputies theorize the toddler crawled to the balcony and slipped
through railings about six inches apart.
