<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cuba-Disarmament 1stLd-Writethru   05-29 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuba-Disarmament, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0848,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disarmament Meeting in Cuba</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with message to Reagan and
Gorbachev. PICK up 4th pvs, `Introduced by...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign ministers and officials of more than
100 nations Sunday adopted a resolution calling for the elimination
of nuclear arms, the Cuban government news agency reported.
   The resolution, approved during the first day of a special
meeting on disarmament in Havana, the Cuban capital, praised the
superpower agreement to abolish intermediate-range nuclear weapons
as a first step toward nuclear disarmament.
   Foreign ministers of the Third World and non-aligned nations
also sent a message to President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev, who are meeting in Moscow, calling for a 50-percent
reduction in the U.S. and Soviet nuclear arsenals by the end of the
year.
   ``In welcoming the progress made in bilateral (nuclear arms)
negotiations, we reiterate the necessity of encouraging
multilateral talks, especially in the framework of the United
Nations,'' the message said.
   The message was carried by the Cuban government's Prensa Latina
news agency in a dispatch monitored in Mexico City.
   Introduced by Cuba, the resolution called on the United States
and Soviet Union to adopt a ``program by stages for the total
elimination of nuclear arms. Also, it is imperative that other
states that possess nuclear arms be incorporated in this process,''
the news agency reported.
   The resolution said: ``We are firmly convinced that the treaty
between the Soviet Union and the United States on the elimination
of their short- and medium-range nuclear missiles and land bases
must mark the beginning of the process that must be consolidated.''
   President Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe sent a message to the
ministerial conference saying that although the current climate
favors a political dialogue, the threat of world war continues.
   In his message, read to the meeting by Foreign Minister Nathan
Shamuyarira of Zimbabwe, Mugabe praised the U.S.-Soviet agreement
signed last December in Washington, the first superpower arms
treaty in 16 years.
   The agreement was ratified 93-5 by the U.S. Senate on Friday and
approved unanimously Saturday by the Presidium of the Supreme
Soviet.
   Shamuyarira was quoted as telling the meeting that the arms
treaty shows that disarmament is possible and gives hope to
humanity.
   Foreign Minister Guillermo Bedregal of Bolivia said Latin
American and Caribbean countries should be non-aligned so they can
help bring about disarmament, Prensa Latina reported.
   Cuba's vice president, Carlos Rafael Rodriguez, was quoted as
telling the delegates that current international arms expenditures
were almost the same as the $1.2 trillion foreign debt of
developing countries.
   The conference had been scheduled to start on Saturday but was
delayed by the late arrival of some delegates.
