<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Korea-Strike     05-29 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Strike,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>20,000 Workers Go On Strike At Hyundai Motor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 20,000 workers seeking higher
wages went on strike Monday at Hyundai Motor Co.'s assembly plant
in Ulsan, South Korea's largest automaker reported.
   Officials said the production line at the plant on the southeast
coast stopped at 9 a.m. after the breakdown of the seventh round of
management-union talks that began May 18.
   The union sought an increase of 48 percent, or $183, in monthly
earnings excluding bonuses. Management offered a 25 percent raise,
or $106, officials said.
   They said Hyundai auto workers with five to six years of
experience now earn about $821 a month, including bonuses and other
allowances.
   Hyundai's daily production capacity was listed at 2,700 units,
mostly passenger cars for exports. The company has set an annual
export target of 450,000 cars for this year.
   The officials said the strike would cost Hyundai an estimated
$19 million a day.
</TEXT>
