<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-88 2215EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spain-Election 1stLd-Writethru   05-29 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Election, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0839,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moderate Nationalist Coalition Leads In Regional Parliament
Elections</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout UPDATE with results after 61.5 percent of
vote counted, adds background. TRIMS. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The moderate nationalist coalition
Convergencia i Union led elections Sunday to retain its majority in
the 135-seat Catalonian regional parliament.
   With 61.5 percent of the votes counted, the party of regional
government President Jordi Pujol lost two seats and kept 70.
   Regional government spokesman Augusti Bassols said the party won
46 percent of the ballots counted in the northeastern autonomous
region.
   ``We have to be very satisfied, after governing eight years, to
once again retain the absolute majority in the Catalonian
parliament,'' Pujol said.
   The Catalonian branch of the Spanish Socialist Party won 29.7
percent of the votes to retain its 41 seats.
   The Socialists control the national Parliament in Madrid and
hold majorities or govern in coalitions in 10 of the country's 17
regional parliaments.
   The Communist-oriented coalition Catalonian Initiative won 7.4
percent of the vote and nine seats, up three seats from 1984. The
conservative Popular Alliance won 5.2 percent, falling to six seats
from 11 seats.
   The Republican Left party won 4.2 percent of the vote and six
seats while the centrist Democratic Social Center of former Prime
Minister Adolfo Suarez, running for the first time, obtained 3.8
percent of the vote and three seats.
   Bassols said turnout was about 60 percent of the 4.5 million
eligible voters in the autonomous region, which includes the
provinces of Barcelona, Tarragon, Lerida and Gerona.
   The campaign, characterized in the local and national press as
``boring,'' revolved more around the personalities of the
57-year-old Pujol and his 47-year-old Socialist rival, Raimon
Obiols, than on substantive issues.
   Since 1980 Pujol has been the undisputed leader of center-right
Catalonian nationalism, which has been a potent force since the
turn of the century in the region known for its industrial and
commercial prowess.
   In the 1960s, when dictator Gen. Francisco Franco was in power
in Madrid, Pujol went to jail for defending democracy and
Catalonian language and culture.
   Pujol has jousted periodically with the central government for
greater regional autonomy, guaranteed to all 17 regions by Spain's
1978 Constitution.
   Like the other regions, Catalonia depends on revenues collected
by Madrid for its budget.
   Since Spain returned to democracy in 1977, Catalonians have
tended to vote left in national elections and center or right in
regional balloting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
