<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Dance     05-29 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dance,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Russian Dancers Appear with Ballet Theater</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With two principal dancers from Leningrad's
Kirov Ballet in starring roles and the American Ballet Theater
company in top form, a full-length performance of ``La Bayadere''
made for an electric evening.
   Altynai Assylmuratova and Farukh Ruzimatov are the first Soviet
dancers to guest with American Ballet Theater.
   ``La Bayadere'' was first performed in Russia in 1877. It was
staged and choreographed, after Marius Petipa, for American Ballet
Theater by Natalia Makarova in 1980. Miss Makarova, who was a Kirov
Ballet dancer before she defected to the West, at that time danced
the part of Nikiya, the temple dancer or bayadere.
   On Saturday night, Ruzimatov danced the role of the warrior
Solor, who falls in love with the bayadere, performed by Miss
Assylmuratova. Then the Radjah introduces Solor to his daughter to
be his bride and Solor falls for her beauty.
   When Ruzimatov entered the stage, he was a coiled spring _ a
slim, lithe man about to burst with energy. An entrance of such
contained excitement has seldom been seen since Rudolf Nureyev was
young. Ruzimatov lived up to that promise with his turns in air,
the elevation of his jumps and the beauty of his technique.
   Miss Assylmuratova has splendid technique also, and her duet and
solo dancing dazzled. However, she seemed tense instead of
conveying freedom as she flew across the stage. One expects her to
relax more for her second performance. Also, she didn't convey the
acting part of her role as Ruzimatov did his.
   Susan Jaffe danced the Radjah's daughter. She held her own in
what must have seemed daunting company.
   Victor Barbee was very effective as the High Brahmin who also
loves the bayadere and whose mime gestures help move the plot.
Johann Renvall was the third act's bronze idol and did his solo in
a dignified way instead of making it look silly.
   The second act, in the Kingdom of the Shades, is all of ``La
Bayadere'' usually seen in this country. Its soothing beauty rests
on the corps de ballet's being able to move in unison and to hold
long, difficult balances. On Saturday night, Ballet Theater's corps
de ballet was exquisite.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
