<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SmellofSuccess     05-29 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smell of Success,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Residents of Illinois Town Endure Stench to Stock Nation's
Cupboards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOOPESTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The smell of success stinks, say some
residents of this east-central Illinois town whose canneries supply
food that stocks the nation's cupboards.
   Each spring residents await the return of noxious fumes that
waft off water used to process beans and corn at two local
canneries that support the town's economy.
   ``I just tell people it only hurts your nose, it doesn't hurt
your lungs,'' said Hoopeston Chamber of Commerce official Rose
Buck. ``That's the smell of success.''
   Millions of gallons of the contaminated water are sprayed
irrigation-style onto nearby fields until winter weather arrives.
Warm temperatures release the vapors and winds carry them around
and into the town of 6,400 residents.
   While canning company officials say special equipment has
helped, the odor leaves many breathless.
   ``There is nothing more offensive than the bean water,'' said
Hoopeston City Councilman Willis Bird, who farms near the ponds
sitting along Illinois Rts. 1 and 9. ``You don't get used to it.
You just hope you're not in that field too long.''
   But the putrid smell _ best described as rotting vegetables _
represents money in the bank for the townspeople.
   Two century-old Hoopeston canneries _ owned by Pillsbury-Joan of
Arc Canning Co. and Stokely USA Inc. _ employ hundreds of local
residents and pump millions of dollars into the area's economy.
Thousands more migrant seasonal workers are hired each year to help
with the fall harvest.
   ``If we don't have that smell, we would be in trouble,'' Bird
said, adding that most Americans probably don't realize what
Hoopeston endures to keep canned goods in the nation's grocery
stores.
   ``They don't even know where a can of beans comes from. They
don't know where milk comes from, or how much work is done to keep
the beans clean,'' he said.
   Nine types of beans come into the Pillsbury-Joan of Arc plant
dry and must be washed and then soaked and softened in water. Most
of the water is then discarded.
   The rehydrated beans, including kidney, garbanzo and black-eyed
peas, are sold to consumers nationwide under the Joan of Arc and
other labels, and used in chili sold by the Wendy's hamburger chain.
   Plant Manager Gary Kortkamp of Pillsbury-Joan of Arc says the
company invested in a $1 million, state-of-the-art water
reclamation facility three years ago that eliminated much of the
odor.
   The system strains the larger bean parts out, then pumps the
water into tanks where microscopic organisms eat much of the
remaining bean matter.
   ``I'm talking about a relative smell,'' Kortkamp said. ``On a
scale of one to 10 we have improved it to an eight or nine.''
   But some odor remains, Bird said.
   ``After they have processed it two or three times, then it gets
into that big lagoon out there. Then they spray it into the air and
it gets a little rank,'' he said.
   In the fall, fumes from water used to process sweet corn
contribute to the odor problem. Pungent corn water then is sprayed
onto fields north of town.
   Stokely sells the corn and a variety of other canned goods under
its label.
   While the scent might annoy some vistors, many long-time
residents say it's all in the nose.
   ``That doesn't stink,'' a Hoopeston policeman said when asked
about the smell. ``I've lived here all my life and I'm used to it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
