<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Rawlings-Helmets     05-29 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rawlings-Helmets,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rawlings Getting Out Of Helmet Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rawlings Sporting Goods Co. has announced that
it is getting out of the football helmet business, citing increased
liability and ``skyrocketing'' insurance costs.
   The company will continue to manufacture football equipment from
the neck down and will also continue to make non-competitive
replica helmets, Rawlings spokesman M. Scott Smith said Friday.
   Rawlings' departure from the helmet business leaves only two
major U.S. manufacturers _ Riddell Sporting Goods Inc. of Chicago
and A.H.I. Corp. of Litchfield, Ill., Smith said.
   ``Rawlings has explored options to make it practical and
profitable to remain in the helmet business, but can no longer
justify the manufacture of competitive football helmets,'' Smith
said.
   Litigation involving head and neck injuries was the major factor
in the decision, Smith said. In the past 15 years there have been
about 25 helmet liability cases tried in court and verdicts have
been granted totaling around $46 million, he said.
   Since 1980, the total has been $39 million.
   Rawlings made its competitive helmets at Ava, Mo. The helmets
were one-piece shells of polycarbonate plastic.
   Most of the company's sales of competitive helmets has been to
high schools and colleges, Smith said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
